text: My favorite snorkeling beach on the island.  I hane yet to find a monk seal here or turtle while in the water but I'm sure it will happen! The current can be really strong here but on a calm day you can snorkeling without fins or floaties. We did witness a near drowning from someone who got fatigued while swimming the outer reef. Beware, it's farther than it looks from the shore!

text:
Best snorkel beach on Kauai (except for Poipu for kiddies)  - consider the views of Napali, best in the world perhaps?

Coral reef is sick but we saw 3 turtles and tons of fish, the drop off is a bit unnerving for inexperienced.

You have to get lucky for the parking is only drawback - even Lumahai east side has more spots.

text:
Parking is indeed crazy - there's a small parking street which takes maybe 8 cars, then further down the road another larger parking lot, at the cave. Trust the other reviews and go really early - 8 or 9 - if you want to find parking.

The snorkeling area itself is pretty challenging - very strong currents in the winter. Lots of fish though, and good couple of areas to explore. Even a strong swimmer might start on one side and kinda fight the current to end up on the other side.

It feels like they have a monk seal on retainer, three days in a row when we went there we saw one.
business_description: Low-key sand beach backed by picturesque tropical vegetation, with shallow reefs for snorkeling.

text:
This is not sandy beach for laying out, and will be a tough climb down for those who have trouble walking. It is not wheelchair or stroller accessible, and one should take precaution and wear close-toed shoes since the trail is steep and slippery in places. There are clearly marked warnings in the neighborhood at the head of the path.
That being said I really enjoyed the views of the ocean from the Spitting Cave. We didn't climb all the way down, but the power of the ocean is very evident in this spot.
The erosion on the rock formations are absolutely worth viewing and are great for earth lovers and photographers alike. It's nice because it is tucked away so it lacks some of the visitation volume as some other nearby attractions.

A must see on Oahu.  Relatively easy trek, however it's a long way down.  Wet rocks tend to be slippery, so be smart...and don't bring little children, unless you're up to the task.
The color of the water appears fake.  As the cave fills with the tide, actually the aquifers, pressure builds and the water is expelled with magnificent force.  Sometimes only a grumble, others....a 75' rainbow geiser
Please like my review, I'm a douchebag but I'm honest!

text: Stopped by this spot on 26 Jan 2019 after a Koko Head Crater trail hike and thank goodness this wasn't difficult to navigate to from the street parking as I was "hiked out" for the day! :)  I do believe it was low tide when we came here as there was no "spitting" action coming from the cave below but we did catch a few dudes that leapt off the cliffs right over where the spitting cave 'usually' would be spitting out and I snapped some great action shots of them taking the leap. I was also lucky enough to capture a big arse turtle making a cameo near the spitting cave. Check out my pictures! It appears that they did not upload in any particular order. I may try to reupload so they happen in order, especially for the 3 different dudes leaping from the cliff. Mahalo!

text: After Kamehameha's death, a hale poki (mortuary house) was built next to the heiau to hold his bones. While the original buildings are now gone, the site has several reconstructed structures and is important as not only the last residence of Kamehameha I, who united all of the Hawaiian Islands, but also as the capital of the Kingdom of Hawai'i and the site were the Hawaiian system of kapu was ended and the first Christian missionaries landed on the islands.
business_description: 1970s reconstruction of the residence of King Kamehameha I at the the King Kamehameha Hotel.

text:
We came here for a birthday party and ate off of their buffet line.  So I can't really say anything about price but I can comment on taste!!!

The food here was pretty good.  I'm Filipino, but like 2nd generation, so the names of a lot of the food I couldn't tell you.  All I can say is that it was all very good.  There was about 10 different dishes and we tried them all.  My son and I liked the pancit and I really enjoyed the calamari and fried fish.  I liked the lecheon kuwali, but it wasn't as good as Thelma's in my opinion.

The staff here sucked.  I was given a soda, but no one ever came back to refill my drink.  The staff serving our side of the restaurant was separate from the normal wait staff.  I'm sure their tip was included in the price to rent the place out, but that doesn't mean that you shouldn't try to earn your tip.  I saw all our wait staff standing around and giggling up in the front and checking their cell phones.

I would consider coming back here again for just a meal, but from what I've been told it's just a fancy Filipino food restaurant.  Combine that with the experience I had with the staff, I would much rather prefer Thelma's to satisfy my Filipino food cravings and save some money.

text: We eat a lot of Thai food, and the flavors seem pretty consistent and vary only a little from restaurant to restaurant.  Maybe this Thai place is from a different region of Thailand, but the flavors were just not right.  The Tom Ka Gai missed those unique flavors that really make it Tomorrow Ka Gai.  It was ok, but not right.  The Paang Curry was ok, but did not have the right flavors and the vegetables were all different.  It had broccoli instead of eggplant and other substitutions.  Maybe it is necessary being on the island, but with as high as the review were I thought they would be closer to the right flavors.  The flavors were ok, just not what they were supposed to be.

text:
Roy's is just off the main highway and easy to find. Ample free parking with views of the golf course. A large waiting area outside was justified, as it seems to be a very popular place. Reservation recommended although our walk-in wait was only about 30 minutes on a Sunday night.

The tables and seating arrangement is spacious but the environment cold and hard feeling. Not table cloth fancy but almost. Staff dressed up but patrons wore all assortment of styles, giving the impression of a casual atmosphere. Service was fast, polite and precise yet lacking warmth that added to the harder edge of Roy's ambiance.

The bar area is ample and well stocked. The sangria was the best I've had on Maui. The wine selection was regionally varied and above the fold.

The dragon roll appetizer was crispy outside, with well balanced flavors that didn't overpower the eel. Tricky to prepare and delicious! This was our favorite plate of the evening.

Our Duck 2 ways was equally flavorful and tender. The sweet sauce is what really shines in that dish.

We wrapped up with a molten cake that was not only beautiful in presentation but more delicious than I remember most cakes of its type.

If your looking for a higher-end meal but don't want to sit in a hotel restaurant, Roy's offers not only a building outside a hotel complex but a view more than ocean with genuinely great menu selection.
business_description: High-end chain serving notable chef Roy Yamaguchi's Hawaiian fusion fare in a contemporary setting.

text: Went here to grab some pupu's with my girlfriend.  The Food was presented well. Some of the butter fish I had was a little disappointing as it had a fishy taste to it, i didnt expect it. Luckily my girlfriend didnt mind and finished it otherwise I would have put my fork down and tried something else. Service was quick. Restrooms were clean and parking was easily available and the walk from the car to Roy's was very short. Servers started off attentive but maybe backed off cause we were engaged with each other. Eventually I had to wait for the bartender to come around and flag him down for another drink. I plan on coming back and trying a full meal rather than pupus. One thing to note and this has no effect on my rating or bias but there were children at the bar with their parents. I have only a few hours away from the children myself so going to a romantic location sitting at the bar and having kiddos around had me on guard. I'm very thankful that the parents that were at the bar with their children had very well behaved children and kudos to those parents for raising well mannered children. Sorry but occasionally I want to get away from the kiddos.

text:
This is one of the most beautiful and romantic places in Kauai.   Seeing the coy ponds, feeling the breeze and listening to the water will make your date even better.  The surrounding hotel is amazingly beautiful.

We had the red snapper and the mahi mahi.  The mahi mahi came out as sword fish. We were not told until it came to our table. We should have been told that when we ordered.

Our fish was very bland in the beginning and slightly overcooked but as the meal went on, both fish took the flavors to the accompanied foods, making the fish taste better and better until the last bite.

For dessert, we had the lava cake.  Great way to end a lighter fish meal.

Hint....  to find the restaurant, go through the main area to the back left.  Go out the door by the wooden alligator.  You will the see a sign.

When we got our food...let's just say I've paid half the price for better rib eye. I must have gotten a bad cut.  We all still had a good time and most of my friends liked their food.  I probably should have ordered the seafood instead, but I feel let down, especially for what I paid.

Such a lovely and romantic setting. Our waitress, Wilma, was awesome. Her detail into my dietary restriction was beyond what I expected- she was on it!!

My husband had the poke for an app and lobster topped opha for his main dish. He raved all night about it!! He also said the garlic truffle butter for the bread was delicious!

text: The restaurant is beautiful and the food is very good. That said, if you are not a guest at the Hyatt expect to be treated like a second class patron. Let me explain. I reserved a table three weeks ago, requesting a view table of one of the many koi ponds around the restaurant. When we arrived 20 minutes before our reservation, dressed appropriately, we watched as hotel guests with no reservations  were seated before us. We were asked by two different hostesses where we were staying. I guess cementing our status as second class. When they finally seated us 25 minutes later we were seated under hot lights in the middle of the room. No view except of other diners. We sat under those lights for five minutes before requesting a new table, preferably a cooler table with less direct lighting. We were moved two tables over, still in the middle of the room but thankfully out from the bright direct lights. The food was good. The service by the waitstaff was excellent. My appetite was ruined by our treatment so I had my wife order for me since I really didn't want to spend any money here. The only reason I stayed was that my mother-in-law had requested this restaurant and we wanted to make her visit to the island special. We were excited to try the restaurant out. Due to the seating arrangement and the hierarchy imposed by the hostesses I will never patronize a Hyatt property in the future. We have patronized many fine restaurants and establishments around the world and have never ever been treated like we were at this restaurant. We will spend our money elsewhere. It's too bad because it has a lot of potential and a great location.

text: It was September second. The second day of the greatest time of the season. PSL season. So I go to my local Starbucks to order my first Pumpkin Spice Latte, when to my dismay, and they tell me they are out of pumpkin spice! How could the greatest time of year be so heartbreaking. The drive thru worker apologized and used the excuse "we are high volume". I don't think she understands that it is PSL season. This is no joke. This isn't a game. This is serious business and when someone comes to the store to get one on the second day of availability, there should be some. If this store is so high volume, they should understand how to manage their stock.

text:
One of the best dining experiences, I've ever experienced.

I haven't had any good Italian food on the island untill I ate here!

They serve complimentary fresh baked bread with olive oil and balsamic vinegar

I'm not a big tomato fan, but the Bruschetta was a delicious and refreshing appetizer.

The Lobster Ravioli is a must try. It's perfectly balanced with fresh lobster and creamy white sauce.

I had the Hazelnut Ice cream for dessert and it's basically the best gelato I've ever had. Think about Nutella Icecream!

The owner Fabrizio, originally from Roma, and is one of the nicest people I've met on the island, very personable. He even escorted us out!

I highly recommend this place, and will definitely be back!

Mahalos, Fabrizio and staff for the amazing experience!

Photo credit goes to Paul Millar
business_description: Cozy trattoria serving simple Italian dishes from a Roman chef in a warm, rustic setting.

text: Driving up to the summit of Muana Loa is a fun and exciting drive.  Please keep in mind the condition of your car and style of driving.  If you have a small car and it is fully loaded, it is not the greatest idea to try and make the drive.  My wife and I had a compact car and it was struggling to get to the summit.  During our trip up, 3 people were trying to get a ride to the top and we had to decline because our car certainly would have overheated.  Also, on the way down.... downshift.  Try to save your brakes by shifting the vehicle into a low gear so you do not need to brake as much.  If you do brake a ton, make a handful of stops on the way down at pull-offs to allow the brakes to cool down for a moment.

text:
After reading a few less than flattering reviews, I have to say I was a bit nervous about my stay at the Kuhio Banyan Club. However,  my concerns were for naught, I had a great time! Upon initial entry to the room, it was fairly clean and well presented. The full kitchenette was a big plus, even if it was just utilised for preparing basic meals and snacks. While the building itself was a bit dated, it certainly didn't bother me. Especially for the cheap price. We were also in need of early checkout due to our flight, and this was accommodated easily.

In short, the location is fantastic, the service good, and the price wonderful. If you can handle not being in a 5-star resort, then the Kuhio Banyan Club is definitely a worthy place to consider, particularly if you're trying to holiday on the cheap.
business_description: Straightforward rooms with kitchenettes in an no-nonsense hotel offering beach gear.

text:
We stopped here on a very hot day in Hilo to cool off.  There is a charge to get into the museum which I thought was a bit steep.

Most of the displays are pretty low tech, but they do have some neat info on them.  My 10 year old son enjoyed reading some of the articles and learning more about tsunamis.

They have a neat vault theater that they show a short movie in.  This was okay, the movie was pretty dated but some of the history in there was interesting.

While this wasn't a great stop, it was okay and interesting.  Best of all it had air conditioning and allowed us to get off our feet for a bit.  There are some neat little shops in this same area that are worth walking around.

text:
One of the best small coffee shops in Honolulu. Aussie-owned ("arvo", get it? Except they are open in the mornings), so yes, you CAN get vegemite toast here.

Accept credit cards using Foursquare.

Fresh ingredients, as locally sourced as possible.

Lovely outdoor seating. Very limited indoor seating. Shares a space with the Paiko flower shop. Often a line starting around 10 o'clock, so get there early if you can.

Definitely spring for the loaded avocado toast, the smoked salmon toast, the lavender latte. It might seem pricey for toast, but no, it's not just toast. Food quality is good, shop is clean, and portions of higher-priced items are generous. Expect the full quarter pound or so of very decent quality smoked salmon on your salmon toast. Food is served on wooden planks, so um, those capers? Yeah, they'll roll, so be prepared to lose a few or grab a fork and knife at the front. Edible flowers garnish most dishes. Beautiful presentation, though often very messy. Order inside, get your table marker, grab an outdoor table, and they will bring the food out to you. Grab extra napkins at the front or bring your own small bag of hand wipes. You'll need them.

Cuppa comes with coffee art, but not obnoxious or interferes with the flavor. Matcha latte is very strong here. If you're looking for a watered-down Starbucks version, go there. They do slow cold filtered coffee here that is very very good.
business_description: Hip, plant-filled coffee shop offering light fare such as toast with unique toppings.

text: Had  a warm matcha latte with my brunch this morning.  Had Avocado toast and meatballs!  Fresh made meatballs with marinera and 2 slices of thick toast.  Enjoyed the chili sprinkles on the toast and dipped the toast into the meatball sauce.  Oh soo good.  Always game for a good meatball and these were good.  You get 3 meatballs.  Service was good and would I come back? Yup.

I'm not a fan of the Lavender latte (it's VERY lavender, like you're drinking essential oils but hey, what did I expect haha).

Also, there's very very very little seating so if you come at a breakfast or lunch hour, or you come on a weekend, expect to wait a very long time for a seat or have to take your meal to-go.

Kakaako's salt structure has parking and they give you the validation follow-up ticket, I love it.

And if you bike, There's a biki in front of it. RIGHT IN FRONT! SO EASY!

text: This small gem in Honolulu is a can't miss for travelers or locals looking for a supremely good coffee or artisanal toast. They pull shots on on high-end La Marzocco equipment, with trained baristas delivering each drink of choice. The avocado and Nutella toast are absolutely sensational, both in taste and presentation. Service was quick and the entire staff was incredibly pleasant. Be sure to stop in for arguably the best coffee and healthy bite to eat in Honolulu!

text: I don't really know where to begin....   If there were ever an experience quite as beautiful and magical as this, then I don't know where else this can be found other than at Chef Chai.   Truly authentic asian fusion crafted with the skill of a pioneering chef!  Sea bass taste was fantastic, the apps were vibrant, and the freshness was out of this world.  But what made this experience even more amazing was the level of service by our server Mr. J and his team.    If not for them, the experience would be half of what it would have been.   We left the restaurant wanting more, and I would have to say bar none, the most amazing experience I have even had in a restaurant.   Should I decide to re-visit this gorgeous island again, Chef Chai would be part of that reason why I would.   Thank you Chef Chai for an amazing memory and thank you Mr. J. for being so authentic and kind.  BRAVO and we can't wait to see you again soon.
business_description: Sleek contemporary venue with a long bar serving Hawaiian regional fare from a celebrated chef.

text: We came here for dinner with a big group of our family. We were seated in the very back of the restaurant in a little private area which was nice. The food was really good, but the portion sizes weren't really large. It was more on the side of fine dining, which means that it really isn't meant for kids. My kids ordered Mac n cheese, but it was fancy Mac n cheese. They did not like it and ended up just eating off of our plates. I got the steamed fish which was soft and tender. My grandpa got the whole fried fish, which he said was delicious. They have a complimentary raspberry chocolate dessert and I also got the cheesecake. It was soft and creamy. No real complaints other than the fact that it doesn't fit kids. Parking is also valet in the parking garage next to chef chais entrance. It is all paid for with validation, but there was only one guy working so there was a wait.

text: Exquisite!  We have not dined here for some years -- just happenstance, I suspect, and were looking for a place to feed a group of ten family and friends in for the Thanksgiving holidays.  Since we had just been to Michel's a few weeks previously, we had to choose something different, and just happened to think of this place because it was close to Waikiki (where most of the group was staying) but not IN Waikiki.  We ordered several appetizers -- four different types,  two or three orders each -- so that everyone would have a taste of everything.  The foie gras was incredible, the escargot and crab exceptional as was the chicken sate with naan and the little ahi poke in cones were so good that I never got to taste it because the others ate it all before I could get to it.  We each ordered whatever we liked for a main course and, incredibly, they all arrived more or less together.  My scallops were cooked to perfection, and since I know how difficult it is to get scallops just slightly underdone, it is a marvel how this kitchen managed to put out all the meals at once and still have the scallops perfect.  I was told the kurobuta pork "osso bucco" was terrific as well as the oxtail soup, although the eaters of that confessed that the other things looked and tasted so good (we passed forks) that they would have eaten something a trifle more substantial had they thought about it.   And, the small deep fried fish -- beautifully executed and the taste to die for.  The desserts were equally up to caliber, although, since I've been on a diet for the past three months, I didn't indulge.  Most definitely a be-back, and I cannot fathom why we were away so long!

text: The food was excellent.   It was very tasty and not something you can not just get at any restaurant.  The seating and ambience was a turn off.  We had a 530 seating in an empty restaurant but hostess sat us next to an already occupied table.  It was obvious they treated us like a "number".  Cause the next couple that walked was seated on the other table right next to us and again...in an empty restaurant!  So they had a total if 4 groups all crammed into 4 tables in one corner of the restaurant, when the rest of the tables in the restaurant were EMPTY.  The tables are so close together that you can hear everyone's conversation around you.  Not my idea of an intimate dinner.  Instead I was left hearing others talk about their family problems or their next real estate adventure. I get that the restaurant is small and they want to get as many tables as they can, but the seating ruined a nice dinner out. My hubbie loved the food, but I won't go back.  The price we paid for a nice dinner should be a dining experience.

Parking is very limited. The lady who helped us was very friendly and helpful. I appreciate a place like this in an area where there's nothing else.
business_description: Bustling, cash-only neighborhood institution serving homestyle Asian eats in a low-key space.

text:
Maybe my standards were a little too high for this landmark local joint I had always heard about but never got to try. It's one of those little hole in the walls run by mom and pop that I usually love and almost feverishly endorse, but the "famous" ahi tataki left me underwhelmed, although the fish was fresh and delicious. I'm going to chalk it up to flavor preference as the sauce it came with was too heavy of a shoyu flavor whereas i usually like it more light with daikon and ponzu.

Regardless of my experience, I still think it's worth a visit to navigate the tiny, crowded parking lot to taste some old school local goodness. Check out their IG for daily specials and call ahead for quicker service.
business_description: Bustling, cash-only neighborhood institution serving homestyle Asian eats in a low-key space.

text: For traditional delicious ramen, this is the place to go. It was a great price for what you got. The fried rice was delicious and stood out. The gyoza, although the stuffing was inconsistent with some having meat and others having almost none, it was damn good. And of course being my favourite I had the spicy ramen. It was very good, traditional and amazing. It felt like I was in a little shop in Japan. If you walk by, you might never know this place existed but it's a must try.

text: It's unbelievable, I know I'm just a dumb haole, but this is the best ramen in Honolulu. Granted I haven't tried them all. Tried quite a few places though. Sometimes the service can be a bit slow... but who cares, what's the rush? Paitan Cashu Ramen with extra noodles is the way to go. The service is very friendly as well. Been here almost ten times now and hope to come back many more.
business_description: Bustling Japanese joint doling out Kyoto-style ramen in a small, unassuming setting.

text: Kyoto Ramen Yotteko-Ya is located on the second floor of the un assuming McCully Shopping Center just outside of downtown Honolulu. It isn't a fancy restaurant but they serve a delicious bowl of noodle. I had the Paitan Chashu Ramen. The broth was savoury and rich and the noodles can be cooked firm (japanese style) or soft (local style). I picked firm noodles and they came out perfect with nice elasticity. They also have a special noodle bowl that is limited. Once it is gone it is gone. If you want to try that one, you'll have to hit them up at lunch.

Well staffed during peak hours and friendly staff.  Food was good by Panda standards and relatively fresh.  Grilled Chicken was by far the best item and they had people waiting for the cooks to make more to meet the demand.  Walnut shrimp was tasty too but not a lot of walnuts.  I'd would pass on the orange chicken as usual as I have never been a fan.  Veggie medley with Tofu was way to spicy.  Drinks were only Pepsi products so that was a bummer. text:
I love this place. The acai bowls are full of flavor (they don't dilute their acai puree with nonsense), the vibe is relaxed and friendly, and the workers are nice. My favorite is the surf bowl (pure acai) with bee pollen and almond butter. I tried to share a large bowl the first time I went, but I quickly learned that I need to eat my own because the bowls are that yummy!

I was in Paia for a couple days (and ate 3 acai bowls in that time), traveled around the rest of the island, had some acai bowls at Choice (LaHaina and Ka'anapali Beach), then came back to Paia on the last day so that I could eat at Paia bowls (and Flatbread) again. That's how much I enjoyed these acai bowls.

text: This is a fun little taco place in Hawaii.  Do you like fish tacos, beef tacos, chicken tacos, and just tacos in general?  Then come on down!  The food is fresh and made to order.  I personally like chicken and fish tacos, but there are so many varieties to choose from.  You can even pick your own toppings to customize your own unique taco. text:
GOOD:  This fast-casual, mall-food-court, local-chain restaurant offers up some tasty food an inexpensive prices.  Salsa bar is provided to dress up your entrees even more.

BAD:  Nothing.

CAUTIONS:  It is not fast-food, it is fast-casual.  Your food is not prepared until after you order it.  After ordering, the wait may be six or seven minutes.  Not a big deal, though.

SUMMARY:  This place is a great choice for fast-casual Mexican food.  I would certainly eat here again when visiting the mall.  I might even stop at the mall just to grab a bite here.

text: This is sort of a hidden gem.  The restaurant itself is not on the street and there's not a big sign with an arrow saying "Come this way!".  As it's in the resort, it takes a bit more effort to find it.  But, you should definitely go find it.  The food is delicious and it looks out on the ocean.  I went to have a breakfast meeting, but left thinking this is a great spot to take my wife for date night!

text: Wasn't as good as the hype. The food was fine and well cooked but lacked seasoning. I ordered the tasting menu which was half servings and plenty for me to eat, but if you're a bigger eater it might not be enough for you.  The tasting menu also was quite pricey considering the half servings. It would have been nice to have the option to change out one of the courses,  but there was a strict no substitution rule due to the half a servings.  Overall the atmosphere is nice and the service was good. We are no strangers to high end restaurants,  So maybe I'm just being a bit picky.  On our next visit we will try someplace else for a romantic evening out.

text: We were there at a Saturday night and they were  probably too busy. After we sat down, looked the menu and were ready to order, we couldnt find any waitress. They were serving foods and drinks, walking into and out from the kitchen. Service is overall not bad and fast, but the servers were so in a rush and we felt so pushed.....hard to get servers' attention. Foods were fantastic, above average, 5 stars, but the service was only 3 stars. Staff is efficient, fast but lack of smile. They looked so pressured, nervous and rushed. The atmosphere in this restaurant is not relaxing but making you nervous too. However foods are well prepared and served. Good to give it a try but better avoid weekends. Michelin food quality but MacDonald pace.

text:
We went and tried Stadium Camellia last weekend after months of talking about it.
It was pretty good. They have a cooked buffet and raw buffet. You can cook your raw food at your table, which is awesome, because you can cook to your own liking. The food overall was pretty good. We had some of everything. The pricing is great, especially considering just how much food you can get. They do have a 2-hour limit, but you can get a ton of food in that time. The service was good. We'll definitely be back.

text: My husband had ordered pizza for dinner so I wouldn't have to cook after work. And we thought he ordered it for delivery. So we waited and waited. He left for work and pizza was still not here. So I tried calling the our pizza store and couldn't get through. So I grab my kids and go pick up our pizza since its been over two hours and we haven't heard anything. No app notification etc. Turns out my husband ordered for carry out and obviously it was our mistake. So I just went into the store and mentioned I was here to pick up an order and the very nice man goes ohh yea we tried calling you ( my husband at work). I very embarrassed respond ohh yes he apparently hit carry out verses delivery. And omgosh OUT OF NO WHERE he offered to remake our pizzas!!!!!!! My son was so happy! He loves pizza hut pizza. Awesome customer service. I was not expecting that because clearly it was our fault we didn't pay close attention to the app but they made dinner that much better! Thank you so much for that awesome service!!! Thank you so much!!!!!! Our pizzas were delicious!!!!

text: This review is not the usual comprehensive eatery review, the reason why may be a little unusual itself. You see I sometimes eat somewhere and find that I like one menu item or side very much and I keep a list of these items and locations. I have what I like to call my perfect meal. I will drive to each location, sometimes putting in a lot of miles to gather the one item I need to contruct my perfect meal, once that is done I go home and feast. The one item I get from this Pizza Hut is the traditional wings (bone in ), well done Buffalo Burning hot or medium. There is something about the sauce? the heat? the smokiness? the tang? I don't know why, but they are currently my favorite wings on the island right now. Try these wings they may become your favorite as you contruct your ultimate meal.

text:
We were in Hawaii to vacation and to visit my family in Oahu.  We stayed in the OHANA Waikiki West, so we frequented this Starbucks once a day.

Like many Starbucks, they are consistent, the staff was quite nice and the place was relatively always a nice and clean Starbucks.  This place will even brew you a fresh cup of Kona coffee for any of you coffee connoisseurs out there reading this.

Overall, it has pretty much anything you would expect in a Starbucks.  The prices are not any different compared to what we've paid in Portland, Oregon.  The only drawback, if any, would be there are no bathrooms.  Regardless, you should be there for the coffee and not the toilets.  Just keep moving--afterall, you're in Hawaii to enjoy the island life.

text: A very friendly cafe with good espresso and now cold brew with cold foam. Outside seating is being replaced soon l'm told.  lt has a lovely view of hills and trees with a steady stream of interesting people and amazing variety of dogs from every "walk" of life.  lf you are lucky you will meet Miss Marly a mixed pit bull white with tan spots who greets everyone and the big grey bird dog that sometimes stops to point with glazed over eyes remembering those old hunting forebears ashe sees a bird. This will necessitate many tugs on his leash before resuming his and his owners progress. The sandwiches are especially good as well as the oat cakes (low fat for me). Very quiet and relaxing place  with minimal car noise.  you might even spot King Eduard of Manoa holding court at one of the new tables. And there's even a man with a cart you can rely on for exact bus scheduling back to town if you take the bus.

text: While in Honolulu, I googled best restaurants near me and best restaurants near Hanauma Bay. Uncle Clay's House of Pure Aloha was on top each time. I had heard of Hawaii's fascination with shaved ice, so I figured I would give it a try. It was well worth the trip. The store itself is located in a strip mall and you have to be careful or you'll miss it, but once you arrive, you can see that it has more customers than any other store. Lucky for us, Uncle Clay was actually there greeting customers. Our family tried a variety of shaved ice and they were all good.  Uncle Clay has all the usual flavors, but he also has a unique variety of Hawaiian flavors. This isn't the greatest dessert I ever had, but I would recommend it for anyone who is curious about the shaved ice phenomenon. Uncle Clay and his team are super helpful and care about the customer.
business_name: Uncle Clay's House of Pure Aloha

text:
We used to love Mailes in Hawaii Kai.
We ordered take out every week.
Lately it's been very inconsistent.
In the Phad Thai Noodles with Shrimp add tofu.
The tofu was cold and raw.
Shrimp tails , sime with no shrimp on them.
Forgot the Chile sauce again.
I always ask for it up when ordering.
It's so unfortunate to see our favorite local restaurant in our area, go down the tubes like this.
Last time they blamed It on the chef being out of town.
But 3 times, is too much.
Another time, a hostess.
I blame management.
So bummed.

I

text:
History: " In early 1843, Lord George Paulet, representing the British Crown, overstepped his bounds, landed Sailors, seized the government buildings in Honolulu and forced King Kamehameha III to cede the islands to England. When Queen Victoria learned of this Injustice she dispatched Admiral Richard Thomas to the islands to restore sovereignty. On July 31st, 1843, pompous ceremonies were held restoring the Hawaiian Kingdom. From that time the plot of land on which the ceremonies took place has been known as Thomas Square. Kamehameha later officially designated the area after Thomas and in 1850 the area was enlarged. A fountain sits in the middle of the park and Banyan trees lend dignity to the foliage."

As a child I frequented this little park and never knew this history until today!

text: Best donuts ever, depending on what you fancy. Their long johns are my fav by far! The filling is sweet but not overly sweet and its filled from end to end, packed solid. I hate when bakeries are super stingy with any filling. My second favs are the old fashioned donuts: original, maple, and chocolate glazed. Don't bother eating anyone else's old fashions. This place has got the magic recipe. Their yeast donuts are very soft and the cinnamon crunch-- total yum. I haven't really tried their cake donuts except the red velvet and the coconut, both of which I did not particularly care for, but there are other flavors that I haven't hit yet.

text: I love Donut King! Market City shopping Center in Ka'imuki. If you know or remember Ken's bakery use to be in Waimanalo. This gives me the same memories going to Ken's in Nalo with my grandma. You can call ahead and order, wear your mask and check sign before walking in. I belive right now they allow only 2 customers at a time. I would wait till 1 customer goes out and the. Head in and check the ground for markings. The dknut are so soft and fresh and tasty. Idk if it's the apple fritters or bears claws but they good. Long John's! YUM! The regulars that my family likes is glazed donut, chocolate donut and chocolate donut with sprinkles, long John's again, powdered cinnamon ones. Try different ones and I promise it won't disappoint. They open at 5:30, I believe.

text: Well naturally I'm all about something that's called Donut King! I mean think about it the absolute Undisputed king of donuts! I bought a gallon of chocolate milk went inside their shop and ordered one of each donut halfway through my gluttonous donut binge , the king himself came out of the king's chamber which is located in the rear of the shop and he was dressed in normal King attire which consists of chocolate-covered cape made of donut skin they were chocolate jimmies and rainbow jimmies sprinkles all over his body he had boots made of the holes of the finest glazed donuts in all of the land he had sparkling frosting and candies which were embroidered all over a gigantic donut crown there was much more but you get the gist of it. He came out from the back to offer me a seat at the table. I'm like what! Me at The Doughnut table? He said yes you have shown great courage and Valor and you have an intestinal fortitude not seen much these days. He said he admired my courage and tenacity in my attempt to eat all the donuts. He told me to get down on my knees and repeat after him. It was something like I promise to uphold blah blah blah blah blah blah blah you know the deal and then I was knighted with a gigantic Long John. Now I am a noble donut night at the king of donuts. No it definitely sounds like I'm describing some type of scene in a gay pornographic movie. But even if I was would you care?

text: Amazing waterfall.  Great hike to get there, about 4 miles round trip.  The trail is fairly wet near the top so bring good hiking shoes.  Mahalo!
business_description: A trail leads hikers to a tall waterfall at this hiking spot known for its picturesque landscapes.

text: Really great hike in a pretty remote part of Maui. The hike up was very moderate as the elevation gain was only a few hundred feet. The trail was wet and somewhat slippery after it rained. The views were very worth the hike. We couldn't find a way to swim in the pool beneath the falls, just fyi.
business_description: A trail leads hikers to a tall waterfall at this hiking spot known for its picturesque landscapes.

text:
Definitely worth the 4mile round trip to visit these stunning waterfalls. It felt so magic after completing the walk and the whole Road to Hana trip.
We got there around 10.30 in the morning and it was muddy but I am so glad we did not miss this stop.
It is a walk uphill the whole way over steel bridges (Indiana Jones esque) through jungle and a beautiful bamboo forest.
Being covered in mud made it all the more fun. Absolutely loved this trail!!!!
business_description: A trail leads hikers to a tall waterfall at this hiking spot known for its picturesque landscapes.

text: Definitely worth the 2 mile hike to see these 400 foot falls. So beautiful. You can go in the water below the falls, and there are a lot of places to sit, rest, and eat before heading back down.
business_description: A trail leads hikers to a tall waterfall at this hiking spot known for its picturesque landscapes.

text: Huge waterfall on the road to Hana. There is a trail to get close to it but its worth walking to. SO soothing to listen and watch. It's near the end of road to Hana, but one of the closer waterfalls near the road.

text:
Kona Coffee Living History Farm is situated on the South West side of the Big Island and a great place to visit. I didn't take the tour inside, but did end up buying a couple of bags of their coffee and mist say it is hands down some of the best coffee I've tasted. The donkey was cool, but no touching! Lol
I will go back next time to get some more coffee.
business_description: Visitors can explore a 1920s coffee farm hosted by costumed guides demonstrating work tasks.

text: This place was not necessarily what I expected but I was not disappointed at all. there are the obligatory coffee samples and small items that you can purchase on your way in, but there are so many more things inside then coffee trees! we were able to visit with three of the different historical interpreters and got to hear things about Japanese immigrant life from the 1920s, how to grow your own pineapples and loofahs, and experience harvesting macadamia nuts and oranges. There are many different kinds of plants for the botanist in you and the interpreters on site will talk to you about many different topics. Beautiful place to practice photographs, learn something new, and have a great cup of coffee!

text: Absolutely LOVED this! I learned so much and was made to feel right at home. They have different people and events throughout the week. On our visit, there was a medicinal man (Jim) there. I was amazed with all that he shared with us and taught me. He took his time with each guest and you can tell he has a passion for what he does. There was also a wonderful lady in the main house that explained how things were done back when this land was working land. It was hands on and you could walk through at your own pace. I would highly recommend this for your next trip to the Big Island.

text: Probably the best place for poke in entire Honolulu. The place is located upstairs with no seating area. Usually there is a line. The staff are friendly and the service is quick. The portion size is generous and the flavors are mouth-watering. My favorite is the spicy Hawaiian.

text: Super friendly, tiny shop on the second floor. Great location down the street from UH. They had about 5-6 different types of fresh poke, which I was given samples of without having to ask. I had a regular poke bowl which came with a choice of 2 flavors and 2 scoops of rice (white or brown). I had the secret and the spicy. Some of the most phenomenal poke I've ever experienced. ABSOLUTELY will be returning and with anyone I can drag along with me! There are other things on the menu but I was focused on the poke bowl. I'm glad I was able to support a local business!
business_description: Small take-out place specializing in locally caught fish for poke bowls with various sauces.

text: Don't be fooled by the outside...best poke l've ever had

text:
My daughter read about Ahi Assassins on Buzzfeed. They raved about what a great place this was and the fish was amazing. So my daughter added A.A. to our must to see list when we were in Honolulu.

At first the location itself seemed a bit sketchy, being that it's located on the second floor of an old motel style structure. We were the only ones at 5:30pm, but the second we stood at the door all doubts disappeared as the aroma of the food being cooked hooked us. My wife and daughter placed there orders for the last portions of Ahi for the day as another family of five stepped up to place their order for the same. Unfortunately they were out of the Ahi, but had plenty of Marlin from the days catch.

The fish was fresh and prepared properly. The owners were fast, friendly and fun. These are a couple of assassins that you must pay to have the fish you love whacked. THE BEST!
business_description: Small take-out place specializing in locally caught fish for poke bowls with various sauces.

text: Amazing, fresh, melt in your mouth poke, definitely one of the best poke shops I've been to on the island and I've been to many. I was nearby and am soooo glad Google Maps recommended this place to me. This little place is a complete hole in the wall but deserve far more attention. The Lunatic is my favorite out of all, the sauce is absolutely perfect. Amazing staff, helpful and friendly. I will definitely return!
business_description: Small take-out place specializing in locally caught fish for poke bowls with various sauces.

text: Their fish is always...ALWAYS on point. Place is a bit hard to find and isn't flashy, but who cares as long as the fish is awesome!

text:
This place is ONO-licious! The first ocean-to-table restaurant, these guys grew up here on Oahu and have spend their lives fishing it's waters. Now, they bring their catch straight in to the restaurant and serve it up! So, I can get fresh fish, from the fisherman, without having to buy the whole ahi.
Absolutely love this place and am thankful to my friend Kenny for introducing me to it.
If you try them, you will want to thank me too, lol. Aloha!
business_description: Small take-out place specializing in locally caught fish for poke bowls with various sauces.

text: I have Celiac disease and I was determined to find a place for me to safely eat poke in Honolulu. They are the only spot in Honolulu that advertises gluten free poke. When I went in they didn't have any available, but made me my own batch. They asked exactly what I wanted and made sure they used all clean bowls and cookware. I wanted to cry they were so kind and accommodating. I talked to them for awhile because of how awesome they were. Uncle Henry told me how the tuna was caught THAT DAY by the owner and he was slicing and dicing it right there. You can't get much fresher than that folks. Come here. Take the bus from the Waikiki area or walk. It's well worth the trip.

text:

We didn't like the Hawaiian as much as it was a bit bland compared to the lunatic and also a bit too salty. We would definitely come back next time we're in town.

text:

Fish selection depends on catch of the day, so it really depends on what they got from the sea to determine what fish they have for the day.

text: The Needle is a stunning rock formation surrounded by lush vegetation and a creek. It is possible to reach an overlook that better looks out to the Needle by walking through a less signposted trail. However, as the climb is steep, in thick vegetation and in hot, humid conditions, bring appropriate shoes and plenty of water.

text:
This place was a pleasant find on my one of my foodie hunts. I had actually seen it in a local news report and thought the food looked good, but when I first attempted to go, found the parking lot full and passed that day. My second attempt was spontaneous, as I was driving by feeling the hunger pains of lunch time calling and the parking lot was clear, so I pulled right in.

That being said, arriving just before noon would probably be a good idea.  Shortly after I Got seated and ordered, I noticed the place quickly filling up and by the time I was leaving, there was no parking. It was a good sign that the place is popular.

They have a lot of Japanese favorite comfort foods that are popular with locals here in Hawaii.  It was pleasure to see they offered the ability to order both off the lunch and dinner menu when I came for lunch.  Many different options and portions to choose from depending on your hunger and tastes.

I really recommend the bento set special.  There are 2 sizes, the lunch and dinner. Which you order will depend on how hungry you, but both are quite substantial and offer a full tasting of different items freshly prepared and beautifully arranged on the serving tray.

Service there was very nice and attentive.  You felt a real sincere feeling from the servers that they care about your experience there.

It was a pretty good value for what I ordered. The quality of food, pleasant ambiance, and friendly service was outstanding for the price.
business_description: Traditional Japanese eats from sashimi to rib-eye steaks served in a casual space with modern flair.

text:
I loved the food!! The prices are reasonable,  they give nice portions, and most importantly the food taste excellent. Not only that, but there is one lady who works the take out section (which is where I tried) and she is very nice and friendly. I haven't tried the restaurant side yet,  but I'm sure it's good too!

I highly recommend! The only thing is they only take cash so be mindful of that. I ordered the Ahi with garlic, ribeye with garlic , and the mushroom chicken (which is there most popular dish). I also got a side of the hiyashi? Hayashi? Don't remember what it's called but it's like a Japanese stew...it's soooooooooo good!!!

You won't be disappointed!

text: Almost all Pizza Huts became takeout stores in our area. The last all-you-can-eat buffet closed many years ago, so when we saw it available here in Kauai, we jumped at the chance to try it. text:
Cool off the beaten path trail. When we went up in the afternoon there was nobody else there. We had to ask someone who worked at the church and golf course where the trail was. When we went up the road to the large water tank (like a water tower, but on the ground) the trail head was on the left right before the tank.

The path is cool and kept up well enough, but also a little overgrown to give you a cool jungle feel. At one point you'll see a tree with a bunch if carvings in it. One if the carvings says "Likeke ->". Take that right turn and you'll get there eventually.

The falls were a little underwhelming, but the hike was really cool and relatively short.

text:
This place gets a 5 star for it's food alone. My family and I have been going their for years and even to their original location before this one and we have always favored their dim sum over anywhere else in town.

The quality of their dim sum far surpasses everyone else for it's freshness and preparation. It is always a good value here, so it won't bust your budget to splurge on a big meal there. They have all the classics and then some for dim sum.

My favorites and must haves are as follows: Spareribs, Siu Mai or Shumai aka Porkhash in Hawaii, Shrimp Dumplings, Steamed Look Fun, Chicken Feet Tripe, jellyfish, Fried Garlic Eggplant, and of course Egg Custard for dessert. Of course there is a full menu of Chinese classics you can order from if you need something more. We like to get a plate of Choy Sum with Oyster Sause for some veggies and sometimes some Crispy Fried Noodles with Seafood if feeling hungry.

Most of the staff have been there a long time and may seem a little rough around the edges, but they know what they are doing. In a a busy place like this, there is no time for niceties and it shouldn't be expected. I don't mean that they are rude, they are just not going to bend all over you like a fancy restaurant.

The place has seen a lot of traffic over the years and it shows it in the overall condition of the restaurant, but I feel that it is clean and never had any problems eating there. Don't let looks deceive you, because if you don't go based on this place's appearance, you will miss out on some really good dim sum.

text:
I Really hate to write a bad review expectantly a place I go and Frequent but there is a problem at this STARBUCKS??

CORPORATE SHOULD REALLY CHECK IN.. Why because I drink so much coffee and I choose Starbucks when ever I can if I have the option. BUT this Store takes the cake for bad Starbucks and I have been to them far and wide ....  There is NO PRIDE at this store the note I enter into when I arrive here is the general feeling of sadness.

SADNESS EXPLAINED:  You walk into this store from a DIRTY out door area,
CUSTOMERS: Then you find that all the tables are filled with sadly the Less fortunate, looking as if they are trying to pull the Charge Leach of the century, this being every table is filled with people who do not plan to leave the shop for some time.... certainty will be there longer than it will take for me to sip down a cup of coffee.

THE STAFF: Sadly this store again sad, seems they go through employees like I go through toilet paper and feel by there looks and how they are rushed and cramped in such a small space, bouncing around because most all new always, this store needs stability. The feeling as I get my change from the Guys behind the counter is SAD and I Drink my Sad cup of coffee.

The STORE ITS SELF:  Ok it smells of coffee and rest room in there ... I do not like to hang out here, the tables are uncomfortable and small limited and are not inviting to share ... I can think a multi billion dollar company that specializes in challenges like this store has not even attempted.
THE BATHROOM is NASTY it even after they clean it has a smell that I would rip the whole structure down and start over kind of smell.

Look I like Starbucks as much as the other and this is a great location.

Suggestions if I may?

1) get better seating as a handicapped person I like to sit and have a cup and inside and outside is nasty.

2) Hire a STAFF and KEEP them ... This location is to small for people who do not know what they are doing there is not room for the extra person to help the new. The staff here seems frustrated and seems to me as a manager in my career tells me there is not much of a leader here.

3) Come up with a schedule of events, put a little stage in and do events like open mic night and poetry readings.

Don't do things like make it even more uncomfortable by removing the plugs or something stupid like this ... Your looking to draw in the crowed at night as you can see the high time to go is in the morning only ...

this place is so perfect for a great neighborhood that will support events But Bare MIN

CLEAN this place, HIRE a staff and UPDATE this store!
business_description: Seattle-based coffeehouse chain known for its signature roasts, light bites and WiFi availability.

text: The customer service was AMAZEBALLS!! Our waitress was upbeat, friendly, informative about the menu and choices, she was, what us locals like to say, ON IT... We got our food in a timely fashion... NO mistakes or forgetfulness on her part... she constantly checked up on us and even made slight suggestions for menu choices when we were indecisive... Overall-- I would HIGHLY recommend this restaurant to any and all passing through or staying on the island... the host (Lilo) was just as AMAZING with awesome Aloha spirit and warm welcomes! Thank you to the staff for blowing our minds with the delicious, off the chain menu! It was authentic, innovative and beyond our taste buds expectations... 5-Star service, 5-Star Menu!!! Mahalo a nui!

text: Very mediocre sushi at best. Coming from Colorado I expected the sushi in Hawaii to be the freshest, most flavorful sushi I have ever eaten. I was let down. I only ordered 3 sushi rolls. 2 if which were very basic. Spicy tuna and a rainbow roll. The 3rd was something that I picked which was supposedly a specialty roll which tasted like overcooked salmon with a nasty aftertaste. The spicy tuna was horrible until I pulled out the thin slices of carrot which they either soaked in some type of pickling solution or was rotted. After taking the carrot out the roll was eat able but with very little flavor. The rainbow roll was the only roll that had a decent taste but was still so bland that I had to soy sauce the thing to meet half of my expectation. I'm so disgusted with sushi on this island that I refuse to eat any more until I get back to Denver. Hard to believe that Colorado has superior sushi but it definitely does. Service was good and I appreciate that. The food on the other hand........... Pitiful

text: Probably the worse moes weve ever been to. We were excited to be near a moes again, so we drove to the otherside of the island to eat there, it was our first time in 8 years. No one said welcome to moes, they stood around talking to one another instead. The girls refused to speak louder, I can hear incredibly well, and I couldn't hear the worker. When I told her i couldn't hear her she spoke even softer, and laughed. An older woman came up behind us and also had to tell them she couldnt hear them several times,  they did nothing to make themselves louder.  They are capable of speaking at an audible volume though, because when the next person came on shift they yelled hey loudly, and then we could hear their convo from where we were sitting on the other side of the restaurant. I'll go back for the queso, but the staff needs to be retrained or rehired.

text:
Regretfully, I haven't been here in years. Not much has changed over the years except several refreshes and the staff. They sure are consistent from when I first experienced Tanaka of Tokyo when I was a kid about 40 years ago and many times since, but for some reason didn't for for a long time until recently. Same great food and exceptional service as well as the overall experience.

This was always the go to place when we had family visiting from the mainland. I continued the tradition as an adult when I had visitors. There is no place I know of that offers a dinner and a show like Takana of Tokyo where the food is actually good. All those luaus for the tourist have horrible food and the settings are not comfortable at all.

I really like how their staff all greet and make sure you feel welcomed and taken care of during your time there. Even the manager pays you a visit. I must give a shoutout to the manager I met this time, Jamie Harada for keeping the experience going and for his professionalism as a restauranteur.

We got the Shogun which I think gives you the best food experience, but if you need to keep it a bit more budgeted, the Daimyo is also a good one to go with. There are cheaper options, but I think you loose out big time.  However, it is understandable that some people can't spend that much or have dietary restrictions.  I do recommend upgrading your meal to include the fried rice over the plain rice if that appeals to you.

So whether you are visiting or local, you will get a good meal here and have some fun at the same time. Itadakimasu!
business_description: Chefs entertain grill-side at this upscale-casual Japanese steakhouse in Waikiki Shopping Plaza.

text: It was such a great experience to go there with my family. The event was to celebrate my best friends wedding earlier in the day. They were able to accommodate our reservations and the table was set up for our group so we could still entertain each other but at a social distance for COVID-19 precautions. The service and the food was absolutely amazing and catered to each of our specific tastes. Seafood. Steak. Chicken. You name it! The garlic fried rice and ribeye definitely topped our list. If you haven't been here yet, I recommend you to go. If it's been a while, i recommend you to visit soon! We cant wait to go back!
business_description: Chefs entertain grill-side at this upscale-casual Japanese steakhouse in Waikiki Shopping Plaza.

text: My wife and recently dined here last weekend and were very satisfied with the service, great food and hospitality. The manager Jamie stopped by our table to express their gratitude for coming in. Being a kama'aina, we rarely get an opportunity to enjoy the Waikiki experience. In these tough times of Covid 19, we appreciate what the hotel industry and restaurants have done for the locals and will definitely return real soon. Our Chef Katsu is the best that we've come across in a decade and suggest everyone from the "808" go see and taste what they have to offer!

text: I have some lovely childhood memories of "showtime" teppanyaki restaurants that I visited in the US as a kid. The food is great as well. I ordered the Shogun special which comes with shrimp, scallops (too small), steak and a lobster tail. Pretty good value if you ask me. I also ordered the seared ahi which was very good. Service was also excellent and fast.

Good:  The chef was great and his food was well seasoned and good.
Bad:  While eating the salad that came before the meal; it felt weird in my mouth. While attempting to pull it out, it ended up being a really long hair.  The general manager didn't even compensate me for my meal.  He told me that he was going to investigate it... Hello! I do not care about your investigation.  Someone's hair was in my mouth!  I only stayed because it was my anniversary and my wife made the reservation.  Never again will I eat here.  It's the principle!  Do not eat here!!!
Edit:  They did comp the celebration packet which was chopsticks and a cake.. oh lets not forget the rice too.  Don't make me post the receipt!!    The hair came from someone and it wasn't my wife's hair if that is what you are insinuating.  Check my other reviews.  This is the only bad review that I have given out in while.  The hair ended up in my mouth, you should have comp the entire meal General Manager.  Maybe this needs to be elevated... I got time today!

text: Verde is quaint little spot to grab some authentic Latin food on the island.  After being on the island for a week,  I began to greatly miss my Latin cuisine.  I am so glad we chose Verde.  Their interior is retro but also modern and fun.  We ate in once and got it to go and took it for a beach picnic:)

text: Verde I saw in Lonely Planet and wanted to go. Apparently I was on a Mexican kick in Hawaii. Have to say it was a stellar choice. Big portions (both of my parents had to get to go boxes), and very fresh. I had the fish tacos - the fish that day was ahi and mahi mahi. I had one taco of each, and both were spectacular. Great aioli, fresh salsa and avocado...just really good food overall.
business_description: New Mexican-inspired twists on Mexican faves draw diners to this casual cafe known for its salsas.

text: The servers were SO nice here! Great customer service, and we loved the salsa and chips. My husband and I ordered taco salads which were good. I think I was hoping for something more like a burrito bowl once I got into it, so I would try another dish next time. Hubby wasn't huge on the dressing either BUT the pulled chicken on it was great. (Really more of a personal preference and at the end of the day we are probably more fajita people than salad people in this case.) Overall, a positive experience based on the great service and we'd visit this location again for sure and try some of the hot dishes.
business_description: New Mexican-inspired twists on Mexican faves draw diners to this casual cafe known for its salsas.

text:
Bull She'd, besides being a fun name, has a great outdoor patio on the beach and live Hawaiian music. I emphasize Hawaiian music here since many places we visited in Kaua'i playing Carribian playlists (weird).

The menu was excellent with all the expected things like a fresh catch of the day, which was perfectly prepared to a fine dining experience. The wine selection varied regionally. The only room for improvement was the salad bar was bland, iceberg lettuce and sadly missing some of those delicious Hawaiian dressings available at other restaurants.

If you can, go to Bull Shed because it ain't no bull.
business_description: Steakhouse serving upscale surf 'n' turf in a relaxed, airy setting with ocean views since 1973.

text: We have eaten here everytime we visit Kaua'i, which is once a year for the past six years, and it is no "Bull Shed", the food is excellent and so is the service! I love the beach, so the beachside view and beautiful tradewinds give the atmosphere a relaxed feel. Although there are many great entrees to choose from, I prefer the Prime Rib which is unbelievably huge, prepared to your taste; juicy, tender and delicious! I am always unable to finish it but not to worry cuz the left overs make for an amazing Prime Rib breakfast in the morning! Bull Shed is so worth going to while vacationing on the beautiful Garden Isle of Kaua'i, you have got to try it! It's ono kine grindz . . .

text:
The good: Food was amazing and the cost was reasonable.  I enjoyed the zucchini fries and the super Gyro. Food came out in a reasonable amount of time.

The Bad: Out of the staff only one member was personable.  Our orginal waitress seemed as through she didnt want our table.  She stated that someone else would help us then said nevermind I'll take you myself.  We started off with soft drinks, my wife drink was fine.  My lemonade came with about "20 or more sugar ants" floating in my cup.  I was very discreet when telling her that I had a cup full on ants.  She said Im not sure how they got there and got a new cup.  That was the last time she came to our table.

The Ugly: Even though I wasn't looking for a free handout, but it would have been a nice gesture to remove my drink from the bill.  Or at least have the manager come over to apologize for serving a cup of ANTS.  Sad part is the waitress that removed our plates and offered to show us the dessert menu was very nice.  I think the other staff can learn from her or hire more like her.

Final note:  thank you for ruining my Father's day dinner!

text: M by Chef Mavro is supposed to be a brasserie... it is less formal than Chef Mavro but I think it's an Asian-influenced take on a brasserie. We began with glasses of Champagne and the Wagyu tartare and charcuterie for 2. The charcuterie was a visual and taste delight; a meal in itself. The tartare was served with delicate chips to use as serving vessels. We would have preferred a raw quail egg as the tartare needed a touch more moisture.  We ordered the American Wagyu and the catch of the day (Ono) for our entrees, accompanied by a glass of pinot noir for the steak and a white with the Ono. Both entrees were visual and taste delights. Service was unobtrusive but attentive. All in all, a great meal at a reasonable price point. Highly recommended!

text:
Innovative and amazing, Oahus top restaurant!

Easy access right off king st is the awe inspiring Chef Mavro. Fresh top notch ingredients combined with true mastery and thoughtful execution. Simple and beautiful decor. It is expensive, but so is a Lamborghini and IT IS WORTH IT.
We had 9 courses and this was the food that must only had originally been served in heaven and like other mythic wonders, man stole them from the gods and brought them to share with mortal kind.

The elysian lamb is worth waging wars over. Hand raised lamb like wagyu are, the meticulous process yields only the finest result. With coconut and date chutneys, the sweet notes sing clearly while the parsnips vadouvan curry and essence of cilantro bring balance and poise to prevent oversweetness.

An epic ballad could be written for each course, from diver scallops to honeydew in champagne gelee.

If theres one place you dine on Oahu before you die, its Chef Mavro's. And If you've never eaten there, you have never truly lived :)

text:
When it comes to finding a spectacular place to dine in Hawaii, you have no shortage of local restaurants willing to cater to your needs.  If you are anything like me you are willing to search for that special place to convey the emotion you feel for the person or people you choose to dine with.

My sisters birthday is a special moment for me and my family so I wanted to ensure she felt like a queen.  I used opentable to reserve that special table, but due to a scheduling conflict I was unable to dine on her birthday.  I placed a call to Chef Mavro  within 24 hours of my reservations and they were happy to reschedule me(FREE OF CHARGE).

My first time dining with Chef Mavro was a experience I can never forget.  On the menu for desert were small carmel candies that left an impression of perfection.  I placed a call to the restaurant to confirm if the candies could be remade.  I was placed on hold and spoke directly to Chef Mavro.  We discussed in detail the menu for the night and he suggested I stick with the assigned menu desserts.

I realized the night of the dinner I would be running late, and placed a call to the front desk to confirm they would inform my party of my tardiness.  "Sure Giovanni we will be happy to entertain your guest, until you arrive."  I was relieved to arrive before my guest and ensure my sister table looked "perfect"

I chose the 6 course meal for us with the wine pairings and could not be happier with presentation.  The highlight of the night was the hand made birthday cake with a single candle.  She smiled in embarrassment but noticed the look on my face as tears  began to stream as the waiter placed a additional plate with 5 small hand made caramels with a simple note..."just for you Giovanni, thanks for coming back"

I highly recommend Chef Mavro for a unique dining experience second to none.

Bravo to the Chef

text: This place was terrible. I don't often give bad reviews, but I can't believe the amount of 5- and 4-star reviews this place has, and just need to add my 2-cents. I ate here for the first (and absolutely last) time this past week and I honestly can't say one good thing about the food. The naan was like pizza dough and there was a TUFT of hair on one of my pieces (like...not a strand...and actual bundle of hairs - I swear it looked like it was from an animal or something). My saag paneer was the worst I've EVER eaten - I've had very oily, somewhat bland, etc. - everyone does it differently and I respect that, even if it's not always my favorite version, but THIS was pathetic. No cream, milk, ANYTHING to make it even remotely runny. It was a stiff bowl of dark green, but somehow had almost no flavor whatsoever. The "paneer" was difficult to find in the mass, but the few miserably tiny pieces I did locate were dried up and brown as if they'd been baked in the desert sun for ages before being hidden in my dish. The meat in the lamb korma was tender (there's a positive!) but the dish again had zero flavor. I've never eaten Indian food (and I've had plenty) that tasted like it wasn't seasoned - now THERE'S a feat! I will not be returning, and wouldn't suggest it of anyone else!

text:
The greatest ukulele brand in the world!

The two greatest ukulele players ever - Jake Shimabukuro and Taimane Gardner - use Kamaka.  That in itself should tell you something.  Then you add in their history and the fact that they concentrate on ONLY making ukuleles, and you'll know why Kamaka ukuleles are the most sought after ukes in the business.

Buy one.  You won't have any regrets!

text: We were very excited to hear about Duck Butt opening up out here in Kapolei close to us.  As soon as we walked in we were greeted by three or four people it was awesome and they seated us right away.  The whole experience was really good my only concern is that on the menu it claims that the food serves 4 people when in fact two people will probably still be hungry with one of these communal plates.  Granite, I eat alot but there was only enough for two people. Other than that it was a great experience and the food was delicious . We'll be back!  Aloha Duck Butt!!

text:
Only one word....YUM!
We tried a few things from the Korean American fusion menu.
Hubby's Kalbi was cooked to a perfect medium and it was oh so tender...geez...
My kiddo had the Terri Burger..5 napkins juicy...
I had the kimchi fried rice and garlic soy wings... Perfect.
My hubby didn't get the IPA draft he wanted because they were out, but the drafts we settled for were cold and fresh. I also tried a house cocktail called the New Fashioned..it was a bit sweet and the smaller ice watered down the drink.
The restaurant is beautiful and clean.
I don't live on that side of the island but I would make the trip for this place.

text:
This was my first time in many many many years visiting the Hawaii Theater. I went for the Mike Epps show on Black Friday. First, I bought drink coupons with the tickets that went to waste because we couldn't bring it drinks into theater area. It would have been nice to know that ahead of time. Secondly, the sound was awful. I was only 3 rows from the stage and we could hardly hear the performers. A few people in the section discussed this with the staff and nothing was down. The HEADLINER, Mike Epps, responded to an audience member and turned his speakers on stage around so we could hear... TERRIBLE...
I liked the pre paid parking and the seats were comfortable. However, it did not feel like the staff was not happy to host the crowd that was there for that show.

text: You might be familiar with Cold Stone Creamery, particularly if you're from the mainland. Sweet Creams is Cold Stone on crack. The ice cream is put on the stone and rolled into thin strips. text:
Following the trendy dessert train, comes Sweet Creams, a frozen rolled ice cream style popularized in Asia and specifically Thailand.

Although I love the idea behind this treat, I was disappointed in the somewhat bland flavor of the ice cream. I had hoped for a more creamy desert but sadly did not experience this. The graham crackers were a bit stale and not crunchy as expected.

If you are looking to try something unique than SC is fun. If you're looking to relive your Asia experience, you'll need to wait until your next overseas trip.
business_description: Compact shop offering handcrafted, Thai-inspired ice cream rolls with various toppings.

text: We made reservations here because we were in the mood for some good sushi. We were arriving a little later in the evening and when we called to make reservations we asked if they'd be running out of food. They said they wouldn't. But low and behold, when we placed our order for the appetizer they said they were out of one of the only items we were interested in. Eventually they managed to find enough ingredients to make one for us...but it was an annoying situation since we had asked when we called. We tried their seafood pancake (delicious) and then their bao buns (fine). We had several sets of nigiri sushi which honestly were not that impressive. We ordered an uzu flavored dessert which was thoroughly enjoyed and a chocolate souffle--a highlight. However, our biggest complaints were the wide variances in portion sizes. The pancake was huge, only one bao bun for an expensive price, the yuzu dessert tiny, and the souffle enormous. You would never be able to predict if you could split something or needed to purchase two to enjoy. The service was also slow. We continued to place more food orders as we progressed through dinner and we were often waiting around for our waitress to come back. Honestly, good food but not really worth the price in our opinion.

The prices were reasonable and I can't wait to come back, this will be a regular place!

text: Delicious food in a relaxed, casual-nice atmosphere. We came here after a long day on the Road to Hana and driving all the way around so we were very tired and hungry! The people here were super-nice (as were most people we encountered in Hawaii) and we had a great time. Pretty pricey, but you get top-notch ingredients and preparation. We started things off with their Oysters Rockefeller Hawaiian Style, served with mango mignonette--divine! I got their seafood coconut curry, my friend got their baby back ribs and we shared a lilikoi (passionfruit brulee) for dessert. Everything was good, but it wasn't quite as good as I was hoping, considering their reputation and prices. My curry was a trifle too bland, although maybe I was supposed to put in more of the "add-ins" they provided for me: golden raisins and cashews, pineapple chutney, and toasted coconut shavings. My friend's baby back ribs were slathered in a bit too much sauce, and she only got a side of mashed potatoes with it--is it too much to ask for at least two sides at these prices? The lilikoi brulee was awesome, though, the perfect texture and served in a bowl made of almond brittle with a disc of nicely caramellized sugar on top, all on top of a bed of fresh berries, wow. Overall a worthwhile visit, but not sure if I really NEED to go back.

text: Our family of 5 stayed in the ocean front rooms in February 2021. The rooms had great views of the flats and the ocean outside the reef. The rooms were clean and the beds were very comfortable. The AC worked well when needed. Most nights were cool enough to leave the windows open and enjoy the sounds of the waves gently lapping the shoreline. The hotel staff were very friendly as was every person we encountered on the island. Having the restaurant within the complex made going to dinner easy with our 10 week old grandson. Live music was played every night and the talent the restaurant brings in was phenomenal. We have stayed on every island in the Hawaiian chain and truly enjoyed Molokai. We had such a good time, we are planning on making this an annual trip.
business_description: Oceanfront property offering traditional island-themed rooms, as well as an outdoor pool.

text:
It is what it is, a cute hotel on the waters edge that makes you feel like you're on Fantasy Island or some through back to the 60's and 70's of ticky tacky postcard scene of old Hawaii that used to be.  It's a complement and not a swipe at the hotel style.  We really enjoyed our stay there along with the layout, room, as well as friendly staff.

The hotel is perfect for those that want to get away, do nothing but relax.  Read a book by the pool or while take an afternoon nap in a hammock are about the most lively things going on there except for the chickens on the property.  The rooms are clean and have just the right immensities to make for a comfortable stay.

There is a restaurant on the property that serves lunch and dinner, but only does breakfast on the weekends.  There is also a bar attached to the restaurant if you want to sit and relax before dinner.  I highly recommend making reservations for dinner as it does get busy and seating is limited.

The lobby staff were all very pleasant as well as the maid and grounds staff.  Everyone smiled when you walked by, which was very nice to see.  It's small hotels like this that can show real Aloha verses the big resorts that train their staff to be fake.
business_description: Oceanfront property offering traditional island-themed rooms, as well as an outdoor pool.
