text: What a little gem!  We went to Napua for our wedding anniversary, thinking it would be a nice place to celebrate.  It was so much more than that.  Napua is located in the Mauan Lani resort complex so I expected it to be just your typical over-priced could-be-anywhere-in-the-world "fancy" restaurant.  I was so wrong.  Napua is owned not by the Mauna Lani Resort but by a local family over in Hamakua.  It's a bit of a farm-to-table operation in that the family also owns a 33 acre farm.  Most of the delicious, oh so fresh food they serve comes from their farm.  Most of the staff are part of the family and all of them also work on the farm.  So the end result is great food, the freshest ingredients, and an intimacy that you cannot find in any formulaic high end eatery.  Our waitress was extremely knowledgeable (she grows the food she served us, after all), very warm and personable.  The food from visual presentation to final bite was excellent.  Our entire experience could not have been more enjoyable.  A unique restaurant, combining the elegance of a luxury resort with the intimacy of a local eatery.  Just perfect!
business_name: Napua at Mauna Lani Beach club
business_description: Secluded resort eatery serving locally sourced, regional cuisine in an open-air, oceanfront setting.

text:
We ate at Napua pre-COVID-19.

RESTAURANT:

Location wise, Napua is one of the best on the island!  The restaurant is covered, but has a large patio and the inside can be exposed to the elements with doors around that open, weather permitting.  At the edge of the patio is a grassy lawn, which leads to the beach.  So, you can see the ocean from any table in the restaurant.  It is gorgeous and extremely picturesque.

SERVICE:

The service is fantastic.  Everyone exemplifies the aloha spirit.  During dinner service, there is often live music.

FOOD:

We ordered the octopus luau, calamari, Kaunamano Farms pork loin, and duck confit.  We had hoped to order the lamb, but they were ran out.  The octopus luau is great to look at and just as delicious to eat.  Overall, the presentation is fantastic and the food is very good.

The shave ice martini is a fun combination of two great drinks!

text:
Food and service were very good. Not that I could detect anything French other than escargots. I would call it pan-Asian with good ingredients and a good taste of mixing flavors.
This is not a romantic place (we came for our anniversary) and the entrance way from the street is positively off-putting. Most of the beach-front hotels in Waikiki offer the same view and many a similar menu. The only advantage of Michel's is that the tiny beach is not crowded with noisy strollers but only a few residents of the apartment complex that Michel's is part of.
business_description: Elegant, classic French restaurant at Colony Surf offering fine dining with beach or city views.

text:
First time visit for dinner. Service was great (specifically Kalani), atmosphere were amazing, right on the beach at sunset.
The food, even though a somewhat limited menu was really delicious.
We ordered the Lobster Bisque, NY Steak and Beef Wellington, plus drinks.
I do recommend trying this place.

text:
I'm into it! Location is EXACTLY what you want in some REAL plate lunch... a spot where you almost couldn't find it if you tried. Like you're 'getting one over' on the locals that keep this place busy!

Selection was pretty tight, and they keep it simple and easy. All the favorite's and some local fresh catch items. Good mac salad, pretty good Katsu, really great teriyaki beef!

Wait was a little long for an order-at-the-counter spot, but so worth it. Picnic tables out front have a lovely view of the loading docks of some industrial buildings... But it still works!

General rule of thumb: plate lunch spots with the odd porcelain Chinese cats waving at you, go there! Seriously: great plate lunch. Second best on Kauai.

As you've seen in most of my reviews... There is no middle ground with me; I either love you or I hate you and you're dead to me.  Other things you should know it's that I'm Vegetarian and I love Mexican food..

Federico's really delivered.  I went there yesterday and again today; I love this place.. We just had the veg enchiladas and a bean and cheese burrito, but it was fantastic.. So much so I went back a second time.

I personally like the simple, laid back environment, but know this is not a sit down restaurant, but it is definitely not fast food either.. It's somewhere in between.. I'm so glad I found this place and gladly give it two thumbs up.

After a good meal the day before, we arrived before closing with numerous people outside having just been served outside to find staff closing early.

The staff said said they were slow and wanted to leave early, and in fact, often closed up to an hour before their posted closing time.

I understand when it is slow, it is tempting to close early, but in a place like Hanalei and the drive that is typically involved getting there, not adhering to your posted hours, is an issue.

text:
To tourists: its just some stones so stay away

To locals: there's lots of mana here so do your best to visit and respect the land.
business_description: Many large stones mark this historical plot of land thought to be the birthplace of Hawaiian chiefs.

text: This is a gorgeous cultural site that should be respected. Please, do not walk beyond the very clearly placed stone barrier and signs that very clearly say to not cross beyond a certain point.
business_description: Many large stones mark this historical plot of land thought to be the birthplace of Hawaiian chiefs.

text:
Beautiful spot just off the highway before the Green World Coffee Farm and the Dole Plantation. It's a little bit hard to find if you are driving, its not well marked by signs, just a gate at a T intersection. There is no official parking lot to access, but you can park on the side of the road on the southbound side near the gate to the entrance. Be careful not to park in front of the gate, it is prohibited. The stones are about a five minute walk from the front gate. There is no staff or any real barriers to entry, you can just walk in.

Went just before sunset when there were only a few other people here. Very peaceful and well preserved spot, if you know the history of it, it feels like a special area where important events happened. You probably need between 15-20 minutes if you walk around the whole area and take pictures.
business_description: Many large stones mark this historical plot of land thought to be the birthplace of Hawaiian chiefs.

text:
Different...
I grew up in Wahiawa- and was always able to go walk around here- we havent been back to look  in years- now u cant walk around amongst the stones. I got scolded by a guy that was weed wacking- told us that u cannot enter- then of course I see that there was a sign by the ground- whoops! It looks great!!-WAY Better than before- but It was weird to be scolded.
He asked if we were locals or just tourists- lol. That was odd too.so I FINALLY got to show my OHA "Registered Hawaiian" Card! Lol...Didnt get me in tho. Lol. So sad! Hawaiian denied entry- even tho I grew up being able to walk around in there -even sat on the stones- I understand tho- gotta protect the Land-

text: A fun stop that is a bit out of the way but definitely worth it. The spouting horn is fun to watch and there's a couple other little holes that also spout out water so watching it is really entertaining. It's also right next to the flea market so there's also other stuff to do. If you're lucky, you'll see some sea turtles. They are gigantic.
business_description: Blowhole frequently spouting seawater up to 50 feet in the air, accompanied by a hissing noise.

text: Fascinating hole created by rock formations. It's pretty cool for about 10 seconds when you see the water shooting out, but then it becomes very repetitive. Worth stopping by if you're on the south part of the island as it's very close to the Sheraton Hotel. We stopped by quickly, hung out for a few minutes, then moved on. The tour buses also stop by here, so expect waves of people to come during the day!
business_description: Blowhole frequently spouting seawater up to 50 feet in the air, accompanied by a hissing noise.

text:
We loved it here. The drawbacks are very little parking space and a huge flea market on the way to the Spouting Horn. There are restrooms but they are the bare minimum. No soap, lots of bugs around. Wear sunscreen and extra bug spray if you plan to video or take photos of spouting horn for a while. Most people congregate in the square. You can see a great view outside of it on the right or left sides. Also, the surf is beautiful to watch to the right of Spouting Horn. Especially during higher tides. Do not pass the signs which say do not pass this point for your safety. People have been swept down and severely injured and died when approaching the surf. You can get good deals from the Flea Market sellers.

To get a good view of Poipu Beach go to The Beach House Restaurant earlier in the day. Or during sunset. During Sunset it is way crowded.

text: We really enjoyed our time at Pietro's.  We got to sit outside for the NY-style pizza.  The staff was very friendly and when we couldn't decide, offered to half each of what we wanted.  The pizza was good, the crust was probably some of the best I've had that wasn't small-batch artisan, and the overall environment was very memorable.  We really enjoyed sitting outside in Hawaii eating pizza.  The shopping center and the road offered just enough entertainment and it was one of our best simple memories from our time on Kauai.

text:
I enjoyed my time at Pita Paradise. I think it is one of the few places that remained open or dine in experience in this harsh times for everyone.

The staff at the reception was very diligent in making sure they have the name and contact info for the group of guests they serve so they can provide contact tracing info if needed. All staff members were wearing masks and gloves. Each guest also had to have their temperature taken before being admitted.

We liked the dishes we ordered as well as the appetizer and drink. The staff serving our table was friendly and kept checking back to make sure we like our dishes and promptly asked if we needed anything.

Overall I like our experience there and would recommend this place for future visitors.

text: This was a fun and interesting hike. Parking was easy to find. The trail was also easy to find. Didn't see a lot of people on the trail. I enjoyed this one.
business_description: Short but steep hike passing several WWII "pillbox" bunkers, with summit views of the North Shore.

text: The hike starts at the Elementary School and is a three-mile loop. You'll see a sign post for the entrance near the end of the parking lot. If there has been any rain recently the trail will be muddy and very slippery. I was able to make it up and down without falling because I was moving slowly and using trees, rocks, roots, ropes and anything sturdy to keep my bearings. Make sure whatever you're wearing, you don't mind getting muddy. The view is worth the hike though! Make sure you visit both pillboxes! The second one is just a little further from the first.
business_description: Short but steep hike passing several WWII "pillbox" bunkers, with summit views of the North Shore.

text: Yes. It is steep, and no.  It is not a quick easy hike.  I am 5 months pregnant and out of shape.  I hiked half of this with a baby on my back before giving in and allowing a friend to carry him the rest of the way. I was out of breath and light headed.  I often leaned against trees to catch my breath and layed down for 20 minutes to let the light headedness pass... but important to note, while it might be slippery at times, there are many exposed tree roots and rocks to get your footing and almost the entire hike is shaded by trees. I agree, this hike would be absolutely ridiculous in the mud or rain. My kids 4, 5 and 8 did great... they loved it! Just when you think you can't make it any further, you're probably just a few minutes from a picnic table resting point and only about 10 or 15 minutes from the first pillbox, watch point.
business_description: Short but steep hike passing several WWII "pillbox" bunkers, with summit views of the North Shore.

text:
Great hike! It's right next to Sunset Beach Elementary and across the street from Bonzai Pipeline.
The first part is definitely work, maybe about a quarter of a mile. After that it flattens out. There's a rope at the beginning that helps.
Our 5-year old didn't have any problems.
The view at the top is amazing. The first pillbox is pretty easy to find. The second one was more challenging to locate. Don't worry if you can't find it right away, just walk through the tall grass. It's one of my favorite hikes, with one of the best views.
Don't leave trash behind.
business_description: Short but steep hike passing several WWII "pillbox" bunkers, with summit views of the North Shore.

text: This is a great hike. Unlike a lot of the other pillbox hikes oh Oahu, which are out in the open, this one you go through a lot of tree covered area. The trail was pretty easy walking, and the view from both pillboxes is fantastic. The second pillbox is a little harder to find, because you have to go past the first one and then down the hill a little ways. This one is definitely kid friendly.

text: Great hike with beautiful views of the north shore. It is located right across the famous Banzai Pipeline. You can spot world famous surfers here. The hike gets a little strenuous and steep midway but evens out later. There are also a couple of viewpoints midway with great views of the shoreline as well. Avoid going if there has been rain in the preceding days. The path is smooth clay and will get extremely slippery and you will get muddy. Bring lots of water as it can get very humid and you will need a lot of hydration

text:
We lucked out and were able to do this trail on a dry day. It's a steep climb at the beginning but on a dry day it's easy. There are some ropes but some of them are so thin I couldn't imagine them helping much if it was muddy. Once up the steep part it's a fairly flat walk to the 1st pill box, the view is nice but it is slightly obstructed. To find the 2nd pill box, from the 1st pill box turn towards the Mauka and look LEFT. Walk towards the giant rocks, it won't look like a path at first but you'll see one shortly. Based on another post that helped up, follow this path but don't get sucked into the mountain side too much or you won't find it. It's not much further

The view is better here, it's not a 360 but it's a nice view of the beach below. We never made it here for sunset but feel like on a dry day this is a totally do-able hike for sunset. I think it took us an hour (?) at a very leisurely pace. We did the hike and an out and back not a loop

text:
A great, moderately difficult hike. Very steep and muddy climb through beautiful forest with some views along the way.

There are two paths, one direct and one indirect. I would recommend taking the left fork, which is the only trail you can really see, on the way up, as it has ropes and good coastal views. This will take you directly to the top.

We heard that there were two pillboxes but were unable to find the second. However, you can see the main pillbox, and walking through the open woods you can see the entrance to a bunker and a few artillery mounts. The flora completely changes on the way up, from beach scrub and tropical plants to ghostly

The indirect path is more obvious on the way down. Head back along the path and you will see a clear trail on the left side that will take you up and then down. This route leads you through more forest and is a little less slick than the main trail, but has no ropes. It will take you past a large open cave which makes a great photo, and eventually merges with the main trail at the bottom quarter of the mountain.
business_description: Short but steep hike passing several WWII "pillbox" bunkers, with summit views of the North Shore.

text: I like this hike, though its not my favorite. Nice quick, beginner hike. It's also most commonly called Sunset Pillboxes. Lots of people go for sunset. There are two pillboxes. The first one is cool, but the second one is pretty popular because it has a peace sign on it and is good for pictures. To get to the second one, just continue on the trail that you took to get to the first one. When you come to a fork in the road, take the right. Just keep going down, you'll eventually find it.

text:
Here is an unexpected find in the heart of seedy Chinatown on the corner of the infamous N.Hotel St. and Smith St.

We stepped into this darkened yet well lit restaurant off the sunny street to find an inviting layout that was comfortable with an eclectic decor which relaxes you from the get go. There was an assortment of options for social distancing seating during this COVID-19 situation, but you can tell that even during normal times, there would be a good layout.

The staff were all very inviting and friendly while maintaining their own safety spaces.  We were greeted immediately and offered seating options.  Hand sanitizer was also available right when you walked in the door from a no touch dispenser.

We came on a Saturday, so there was only the brunch menu available. It was a bit of a disappointment, but our fault for not checking first.  There were adequate options to choose from despite not having the full lunch menu available.

I ordered the Tavern Burger.  The burger was probably one of the best gourmet burgers I have ever had.  Cooked to perfection, they got my order of medium rare perfectly.  Everything from the bun to the accudiments were all put together for a picture perfect burger that was very delicious. The only disappointing part of this dish were the french fries. Not sure what it was, but they just were not very good. The fries were limp and didn't seem to have been cooked properly.

My partner got the lobster roll.  Although the lobster was excellent and generous, there was just something missing about this sandwich.  It needed something more to the lobster and mayonnaise and seemed incomplete.  I think if you were a minimalist for food who like thing plain, you would like this dish.

All in all, it was a good experience and would recommend others to try it.

text:
Bottom Line: Good Drink, 1 for 2 on the food, inconsistent service, hesitant to recommend.

We started with the Hen of the Wood Mushroom, which was fantastic. The fried pork belly and asparagus were great accents.

The old fashion was recommended by the waitresss an didn't disappoint. The bitters were the perfect accompaniment to the bourbon. Although the menu stated that the bourbon was Livestock selected Maker's Mark...it was actually Elijah Craig? It was even printed as Makers on my receipt...Either way, well executed besides the confusion on what's inside.

We selected the leg of lamb as our main. The lamb was sliced thin and seared. This led to the meat being overdone and jerky like. I think it would been executed better as a roast ad cut to order. Some of the vegetables were underdone. Overall a promising dish that underwhelmed.

One strang side note, the bathroom soap was way overpowering, interfering with the taste of my drink and meal.

I would've liked to share these issues with the staff, but I wasn't asked how my meal went.

Overall, I would be hesitant to recommend this restaurant...as the issues I experienced seem to be apart of the normal operation. It is the little things that matter when paying chef quality prices...

text:
Great place for dinner!  It's located in Chinatown which is a bit sketchy for those who are visiting Oahu; it reminds me of the LA arts district or SF Mission district.   Hipster places popping all over and gentrifying a otherwise undesirable location.   I suppose you can call the area gritty.   However, it was a convenient straight shot 25-min bus ride from our hotel in Waikiki.

A local took us here and introduced us to Livestock Tavern -- I would definitely visit again.

We had the octopus appetizer. I generally don't eat straight up squid of octopus unless it's in takoyaki or fried to a crisp in calamari so having grilled octopus was interesting.  The texture was very soft which I hear is hard to achieve with octopus.

For the main course, I had the braised short ribs which were off the charts tender and flavorful.  It's a definite reorder the next time I visit.

Lastly, we had the chocolate mousse cake which was simply divine.

Service was wonderful.

text: This place has a vibrant atmosphere. The wall decor is bold and interesting. The staff is very friendly and polite. At night they have live music performed by local artists. However, they should work on their accoustics as it gets very loud an indistinguishable at some point. So be prepared for that.

text: Thoroughly enjoyed open mic on Thursday, here. Amazing ambience, chill crowd, close-to-perfect long island iced tea, with live music afterwards. Definitely a place for relaxed grown ups to lounge. Be sure to peep tbe Dragon Upstairs, and Enjoy!!
business_description: Classy jazz club hosting a diverse lineup of acts in cozy, Asian-accented digs above Hank's Cafe.

text:
This bar has a jazz New Orleans feel to it and the location makes you feel like you're in an exclusive bar upstairs away from the street. If you come at the right time you can see the live band play some great music while you relax with your friends. When there is a band make sure to bring something for them. The bar has a cover charge when a live band is playing. Its not a lot and its supporting the local talent.

A few negatives though. The bar is upstairs so that hinders handy capable people or people not very good with stairs. The bathrooms are small and only meant for one person at a time. Male and female bathrooms. If you want or care about beer on tap, they don't have any. But they do have bottles and an good assortment of liquors.

Both a negative and a positive, there is a good amount of parking down the street. but it is paid parking. So keep that in your budget or get a ride.

But I would definitely recommend this bar. But I like the grunge New Orleans look.

Mr. Carlyle

text:
Okay, so I went with two older ladies who are Visayan and have been there apparently quite a bit. So yeah, we might have gotten more preferential service than if I went alone. But, the service was very sweet in general, even with the other tables I noticed. Biggest lure seems to be the all you can eat buffet. It's a pretty small one, though.

Lechon Kawali was bright and fresh and the skin was well rendered. Lumpia was crispy and not overly greasy; sauce was basic but a nice complement.

The Halo Halo is the size of a child's head, so be prepared to eat something very cold very quickly. Not really an individual kind of serving. Then again, maybe that's all you want for the day. In which case, yes, it's an individual serving. ;)

A pretty clean and bright, if old, establishment.

Bathroom available on site. Unisex and just the one though.

Free parking, although it gets very tight. Be prepared to park on-street in the little road in front, running parallel to Farrington Highway, during dinner hour.

So we wait and wait one other employee quotes us a price for a side item.  We get our other items and proceed to checkout.  At the checkout the girl tries to charge us twice as much.  I ask for the manager and guess who shows up the girl that started this by  giving away all the food that was on the line.  Then she asked the other girl what she told us she told her and still didn't give us the side dish for the quoted price. This after giving away over a hundred dollars worth of food.
Poor service, great tasting food, poor front of the house training as well. Sad that there is only one of these restaurants here on island.

text: Vegan food with Asian flavors, no MSG, very clean. Lots of stir fries with rice, the BEST vegan pho (even better than beef pho from other places,) vegan summer rolls with "shrimp" and crispy spring rolls that won't have you missing the meat. They even have an appetizer that looks like chicken nuggets but is vegan and quite delicious. Their vegan take on banh mi is really good! If you're occasionally wanting to eat vegan or are a vegan looking for a new place to eat, try Loving Hut, you won't be disappointed!

text: I love this place! We eat here as often as possible. The food is a fusion of many styles and served as family style (if you want to share). Very popular and reservations are highly suggested. The wait staff is friendly and helpful with suggestions. They will let you know if you are ordering too much food (or not enough!). We never leave hungry or unsatisfied.

text: I have been looking forward to eating here for a while. Huge Iron Chef nerd. We had a reservation at 8 and got seated soon after. Service was incredible and the ambiance of the place was fantastic. We ordered a little bit of everything and the portions were perfect for 2. Food was delicious and presentation is just what you would expect when you put your fancy pants on and go to a place like this. Would highly recommend Morimoto Asia.
business_description: Sleek, modern eatery offing high-end Japanese fare by Iron Chef Masaharu Morimoto plus cocktails.

text:
We had such an excellent meal here. The dining area is gorgeous. View of the water on Waikiki Beach so you can watch the sunset. Open kitchen concept so you can see what is happening. High ceilings and nice space between the tables.

For drinks, they have a few specialties. The smokey Manhattan is prepared at the table and a great version of the drink. The slushy Kiran is refreshing but a little strange.

For our appetizers, we tried the short ribs and dim sum sampler. Both were excellent and great for sharing. Really loved the short ribs!

For our mains, we shared a rainbow roll, Kung Pao Chicken, kalbi short ribs and chef Morimoto's signature dish (buri bop). Everything was excellent! Great for sharing! The buri bop is prepared at the table and is super fun to watch.

For dessert, we have the chocolate sphere and donuts. Beautiful presentation and delicious!! The sphere is prepared at the table as well.
business_description: Sleek, modern eatery offing high-end Japanese fare by Iron Chef Masaharu Morimoto plus cocktails.

text: Great atmosphere, food, libations, and awesome staff.

text:
Three stars.  If you have watched Morimoto on Iron Chef America,  you will notice his clean yet excellent choices of meal on the show.

We were expecting similar clean and unique dishes at a restaurant that bore his name.  Sadly this is an Americanized restaurant.  Dishes are designed to cater the tastes of the masses.

I believe Morimoto may have a unique shop else where that focuses on his trademark clean and unique dishes.  But the Waikiki location is on part with the usual Asian style restaurants.

It's good and worth your money, just don't expect dishes like Morimoto would make on Iron Chef America.    Bon Appetit!

text: The hike over here was a little tough. It was a little rainy that day so the trail was a little muddy. The trail was probably a mile long. It was alot of up and down. text: I love this hike for an adventure and nice swim after. From my impression Oahu doesn't seem to have as lush waterfalls as some of the other Hawaiian islands. This one is an exception. My husband and I have hiked there 2 times previously trying to find the waterfall and missing the correct turn. You access the falls from the Manana Trail. This trail leads you down the valley, watch out for tree roots there's plenty of them to stub your toes on. There comes a fork in the trail about 45 to an hour in where you can either go left and up or right and down. GO LEFT! Previously we had always thought to take the trail going down because we thought it would lead us to the falls. Take the trail on the left going up trust me you will get there. Once you reach the falls there is a lot of rope climbing down the rocks to get to the pools below. The water was cold but so refreshing! They also have ropes so you can swing, landing in the water, which is deep enough to do safely. This hike can get very muddy, I recommend hiking barefoot since it's much easier than slipping around in shoes. Definitely one of my favorite hikes so far.
business_description: Dramatic cascade tumbling into a rocky pool popular for swimming, reached by testing forest trail.

text:
After the somewhat arduous hike the Cold mountain water under the waterfall was like heaven. It was rather crowded, but the majority of people there were attractive and friendly. So that was nice.

There are two large pools and one small one. To reach the pool directly underneath the waterfall you have to kinda rappel down this knotted rope someone left there. The rock is muddy and a bit slippery so you have to be careful, but it's honesty not that far of a drop anyway.

text: A fairly straight forward hike (1.5 miles to falls). Stay to the right at the first to signs, then on the otherwise and towards the bottom of the hill the trail   becomes a "T" and you can go left (the quicker route) or right (you will have to turn left at the bottom of the hill and follow the stream up to the falls). There is a trail to the left of the first falls that leads you up to the larger falls, but the best views are at the bottom anyway. Great place for a swim if it's not to crowded.

text: I too am from Utah,  would go here again if I get the chance. I love Thai food and have learned that what some places call mild,  others call medium. If you say mild in one restaurant that is food with a slight spice,  enough to feel,  not to burn. Others you say mild and it's got no spice at all,  feed the noodles to anyone. This restaurant is the latter. It's not a bad thing at all,  but just something to know so you get your order the way you want it on your first visit.
business_description: Outpost of local Thai chain serving classic cuisine with a kick in a casual, yet refined space.

text:
An upscale Thai restaurant.
Friendly staff,  good food and drinks
business_description: Outpost of local Thai chain serving classic cuisine with a kick in a casual, yet refined space.

text:
Our office recently discovered another Thai place in Mililani and we have been going back and forth between them.  We finally decided that for most of the food, we prefer the taste and cost of the other place but no one can beat Phuket Thai on their fried chicken and calamari (neither of which I consider Thai food).  So while this place has decent Thai food, it's a bit more expensive than the other place (probably because we are paying for the ambiance of eating in a restaurant whereas the other place is mostly take out), we still will consider this place for gatherings.

The fried chicken here is just so good.  I don't know what it is about it.  It has a nice batter on it that's not too overpowering, and the chicken is always juicy.  The calamari is the best I've had anywhere in Hawaii so far.  The breading is minimal but the calamari itself is always perfect.  Most places I have been to, the calamari tends to be super dried out and hard or rubbery... or both.  Not here.  It's soft and perfect!
business_description: Outpost of local Thai chain serving classic cuisine with a kick in a casual, yet refined space.

text:
Broke Da Mouth! Is what we say in Hawaii for outstanding taste!

Although there was a short wait to be seated due to the packed restaurant...I can now see why!  The food is simply delicious!  The menu is short, consise and offers a first rate culinary parade of hits to make your stomach smile.

This was my first trip there, so it was a breakfast trek as it was early in the day.  I had the cheesey grits with bacon and eggs and also ordered a side of the smashed potatoes.  It was mind blowingly good is all I can say for such a simple dish!  My friend had the grits with eggs and shrimp and it was on par and cooked to perfection.  The presentation was outstanding and the portions prefect for the reasonable price.  The champagne mimosa's were a great treat to the dishes for breakfast as well.

I Highly recommend this fine and upcoming restaurant and look forward to trying other dishes here in the future!!

text: This heiau is a magical spot which many miss, which in some ways good as it is more preserved and protected with fewer visitors. The caretaker of this heiau is a good friend and one of the realest Hawaiians that I know.   One of the few sites in Hawaii where you can ocassionally see Hawaiian petroglyphs (when not buried by sand). Wailua Bay is, in of itself, well worth the visit. If you visit: please respect all heiaus and never go inside the rock walls or any areas marked kapu (keep out) Never take any rocks. Also pack all trash. Mahalo!

text: We came here for lunch on a weekend. It wasn't very crowded. They have some strict covid protocols in place, which is great to see. The iced coffee was delicious with the right amount of sweetness. It is one of the best Thai restaurants I've been to. Loved everything about this it! text: I try and go here once a week or every other week for lunch. Their noodles and noodle soups have just the right amount of veggies to noodle combination. You can ask for it to be mild or medium or hot spiced. I usually go for the medium and it is perfect in my humble opinion. I am always greeted by their friendly and courteous staff and I am always seated right after walking through the door. It gets quite busy there doing lunch hour and I imagine dinner, although I have never been to dinner there because I just can't wait long enough for dinner hour to roll around. I want my medium spiced Tom Yum noodle soup with shrimp NOW and a glass of water rounds out a perfect lunch. Delicious food full of flavor. Great friendly staff makes you feel like you matter to them. They will even remember your order if you go for the no fail same as always order as I do. Give it a try. Find a parking spot in either the lot below or off to the side. It is a popular spot so sometimes you have to really look or wait for a stall to open up, but you will glad you did.

text: With the exception of a watery and somewhat sour Tom Kha Gai, everything we had at this restaurant was delicious. The service was good although, as the evening progressed, it got very busy and they didn't seem to have enough staff. Come at six and you can get a table easily. An hour later you will have a wait. However, those who they did have were very charming. The portions are relatively small with lots of well-prepared vegetables, but the desserts are large especially the fried ice cream which gives you two huge balls and is very much sufficient for two people to share. Pad Thai as generous as well, but I could strongly taste the bacon grease in which it was cooked. The salmon was excellent as were the prawns and scallops. The latter was only three prawns and two scallops so it can be awkward for sharing, which we like to do when eating Asian food.We will definitely  be back!

text: Our dinner was delicious here, it just wasn't the same caliber as some of the other excellent options on the island, although it was one of the most expensive.  The food was solid and nicely presented, the atmosphere was a little funky (really low seats and tables weren't especially comfortable), and the service was...OK.  The front of house service was excellent.  Our waitress seemed tired and not very personable compared to the exceptional service we had at other places on the island.  It was very expensive, which you'd expect in Wailea, but for the very high pricing most places deliver the trifecta of service, atmosphere and food quality.  Maybe it was an off night.

text: Located at Wailea Beach Resort, this restaurant offers both convenience and stunning views.   The cauliflower appetizer was fabulous! My colleague had the calamari. I asked about getting the ramen dish without the fish,  but the server (who was knowledgeable and helpful) advised against it.   My colleague ordered the ramen with fish, while I opted for a sea scallop and polenta dish.  Other notes: we ate in the lounge area, as no tables were available.  The mood is upscale resort - not noisy,  but great for conversation.   Service and plating were both outstanding,  as one might expect at any Roy's establishment.

text:
We wanted some good down to earth Chinese food so was anticipating some great food. We walked it all the diners were on the lanai side so we were promptly seated after clearing a table for us.  The place is well decorated and open. However it's a bit warm with air conditioning inside for guests that don't like the heat.  But the temperature cooled down a lot after our dinner.

Dishes on the menu covered a lot and staff recommended the fish but we weren't into it. Other diners seems to enjoyed it a lot.

Like usual I always go with a basic wonton soup if they have it.  A good Chinese Restaurant should be have a decent wonton soup right? Gau zi or gyoza, Garlic eggplant, stir fry beef, Singapore rice noodles,  salt and pepper shrimp.

We waited over 20 mins to get the soup, a long for something simple.  Like many restaurants they used the thick noodles which not made for wonton soup. Wonton loosely means swallowing clouds so it should be lite. Soup itself is completely bland. Just tasted like vegetable blanching water. It should have nice flavor broth either seafood or chicken,  hint of white pepper and some crunch greens. To my horror the filling is sliced lapchiong (cured dried Chinese sausage). Again should have lite (cloud) texture with minced pork and some shrimp.  NOT scraps!

Gyoza dough were undercooked though filling tasted good.  Not sure it's store bought...

Singapore fried noodles was still very chewy. A result of not soaking the rice noodles long enough and add hardly any curry tastes. Curry the flavor the dish is known for.

Other dishes ordered all have wonderful fragrance when they were served but all too salty. Even though smelled great but all I can taste was salt. Everything was too oily.

I read the other reviews about how they contacted with tour guides. If this were true it's totally unethical especially the kids now also have to learn and lie about it.

We might give then another try but not as what I would consider a good restuarant that have serviced Lahaina for many years.
business_description: Familiar Chinese eats in a relaxed setting, plus front porch seats across the street from the beach.

text: Amazing service and food. We wanted to seat outside and it was lovely. Food was so flavorful. I tried the Papio and to be honest I'm not a fish person but this dish was amazing! Son many different flavors, fish was mild and just delicious. Everyone was exceptional and so cordial. A great experience. Quiet and chill place too so perfect for couples that are trying to stay away from loud crowds. Fantastique!
business_description: Plantation Inn restaurant serving locally inspired French fare in romantic, indoor-outdoor setting.

text: Perfect place to enjoy Thanksgiving. E was a little bummed that they had a special menu because she was looking forward to having Escargot, but she kinda got over it with her meal. We started with the chilled cucumber soup with goat cheese and frozen tomato puree which was something we enjoyed but probably wouldn't think to order. It definitely cooled us down. E got the duck with cannellini beans with ham which she ate to the bone, grandpa had the pink snapper, which he said was a bland fish, however he liked how the capers added such beautiful flavor with the spinach and the rest of his dish, and I had the beef filet which was more medium then medium rare, but was good because of how it was sauced and the sweet potato mash was a winner, so much so that E ate half of it and then asked is this sweet potato? Normally she avoids sweet potatoes at home. And dessert... Creme Caramel and Gateau Chocolate (sp?) were perfect. I loved that the chocolate cake had macadamia nuts in it with the coconut ice cream and raspberry puree. E loved the meringue shavings on her creme Caramel. Patio was nice too...
business_description: Plantation Inn restaurant serving locally inspired French fare in romantic, indoor-outdoor setting.

text: Gerard's is situated in an 9ld plantation style house with a large porch. The food was fresh, well seasoned and cooked. My wife had scallops which were easy to cut with a spoon and were cooked so they were tender and not dry at all. I had the fish of the day with a cream sauce, capers, and mashed potatoes infused with carrot that was piped onto the plate. The server was nice and efficient. The desserts were delicious and probably our favorite part. We were full without being stuffed and hating ourselves with our main entree and 1 dessert to share. My only negative was the bread. It was dry and looked like it came from a super market and the butter was cold and hard to spread. It was free so not a huge deal. I would just say at the caliber of Gerard's either do it well or don't do it at all. Overall, solid meal that we enjoyed the taste of, the service, and the atmosphere.

text: This place gets it all right. First off, while no shaved ice place could be categorized as healthy, this place gets as close as possible with its no artificial flavors or colors, no high fructose corn syrup, and fresh fruit included. The Lava flow (pictured below) was delicious and I would certainly recommend it. Furthermore, the portions are perfect for two to split.

text: This is my first time trying Hawaiian shaved ice and it was yummy. I tried the orange dream and it was heavenly. Especially with their signature Haupia foam (which you ought to get as an extra topping if what you order doesn't have it). The perfect shack for a hot day. Not cheap but worth it
business_description: Chill food truck with picnic tables serving various flavors of shaved ice plus assorted toppings.

text:

Definitely a must try!!!

text:
This place currently holds the title for best shave ice I've had in Hawaii. We haven't gone home yet, so the big island still has a chance.

I completely messed up ordering here, but it was still amazing. There is small print on the menu saying you can add ice cream and I missed it (rookie mistake). Then they apparently have Lilikoi as a secret menu item since someone after me asked about it and ordered it even though it's not on the menu.

Poor ordering skills aside, I got Da Mango One and it was delicious. The ice was shaved perfectly (very fine). Their purees and syrups were handmade. When I got to the bottom of it there was actually extra syrup so no plain ice. I love mango too, so it wasn't all bad even if I didn't get Lilikoi.

My husband got the Almond Joy and loved that as well.

I only wish I had come here before our last day in Kauai so that I could have come back again. Make sure to check them out!
business_description: Chill food truck with picnic tables serving various flavors of shaved ice plus assorted toppings.

I still can't decide and have just come to the conclusion that I like them both for different reasons.

Hee Fat is more traditional shaved ice, refreshing and delicious, but get the real fruit! Worth it.

Wailua is more like a desert, it is a creative piece that is very much different than Hee Fat.

Heck, just do what I do and get them both each time! Can't go wrong with more shaved ice! Nom nom!

text: I first went to La Spezia last July.  I really enjoyed the food, service and ambiance.   I've since recommended it to several people.  In my job, I find myself frequently in a position to make such recommendations.   Tonight I suggested my daughter and her boyfriend go there for a romantic dinner on their last night in Kauai.  Huge mistake on my part. They checked in with the host by 6.30, and were told to expect a 15 minute wait.  After watching multiple groups who arrived after them get seated, they were seated around 7.15.  When they inquired two different times about the wait, the host was cut and dismissive.  Waitress was minimally attentive,  and when finally served, ravioli was cold and veal was marginal.  My daughter and her boyfriend have both worked as wait staff, and are very sympathetic about busy nights in restaurants.   However, they feel they were treated indifferently, perhaps due to their age  (early 20s), and a mistaken impression that they would not tip well.  I was disappointed in their evening, and embarrassed by my recommendation.  Sadly, I can no longer suggest patronizing this establishment.

text:
Depending on if the owner of the condo uses the on site management company, it can add to some extra stress. We had the washing machine break in the condo we rented through VRBO while we were staying there, and when we went to the management company, they wouldn't help at all. Makes sense since the owners of the condo are taking business away from the company. We had to deal with the owners on the mainland while we were stuck with a mess. They accused us of having broke their washer and dryer since it had worked for them for the five months they wee staying there.  When we finally convinced the owners that we are not idiots and their washer just broke, they finally started to work to get a repairman out.

On the plus side, owners can charge less to allow people to stay in their condo when they don't have to pay the management company. Makahuena is a terrific value, and the point is gorgeous at sunset.

text:
After a morning visit to Haleakala National Park in the morning and a few more site seeing stops along the way Westward, this place is must do for lunch.  Their small but fantastic menu of farm fresh meats from the ranch is just amazing.

We had been here 5 years ago and I enjoyed an incredible elk burger, but they were out this time, but to my pleasure, enjoyed a venison hamburger steak.  To me honest, I regretted not getting it as a burger, but it enjoyed it all the same.  They grill up a generously sized venison patty cooked perfectly at medium rare.

I was also very pleased with their version of macaroni salad.  It was the normal bland mayo, pasta, and a few shreds of carrot.  It was a tasty and well prepared salad side that went well with the meat.

There was also a lilikoi cheesecake bar that was very good.  They don't make it themselves, but it is from friends of the owners, so all local.

After you grab a bite, walk across the street to MauiWine and enjoy some local spirits.  If you arrive at 1:30pm, there is a walking tour of this historic estate that is very nice and informative.

This is a must do for sure and really recommend it.

text:
Always good food, however went here 2 times the last 2 weeks and they messed up something on each burrito.

My wife can't handle spicy things but I can, so first they took her order then mine.

I asked for spicy salsa in the burrito but they put it on hers too.

By the time she found out a few bites in eating it she was sick and nauseous.

One week you forgot to put her guacamole on the side and left it out completely, the next week you poisoned her with spicy food which she takes heartburn pills for.

Not going back with the c team working there now, they used to be great.  But not during covid.

text: This place has gotten our food wrong every time we've been. But I doubt getting a correct order would help. The food is just bad. Never had the fish tacos, because they aren't serving them right now. But the burritos are maybe the worst I've ever had. Many good places are struggling to stay in business. It's not fair that places that have bad food, AND mess up your order EVERY TIME, AND have sloppy employees that are either stoned or simply incompetent to make a 5 ingredient BURRITO, AND require masks inside that the employees AREN'T EVEN WEARING. I'm not upset about requiring masks, it's the law right now, and the right thing to do. Why aren't the employees even following the rules they put on their doors? Save your time, money, and frustration. I would give zero stars if I could.

text:
We visited on a Monday early evening. The employees were very helpful and courteous.
I had the super nachos with shredded pork which I didn't particularly care for. It had way too much cheese (the cheese is shredded which they microwave when they prepare it). I think ground beef would have been a better meat selection instead of the pork. I really like the nachos at Taco Del Mar.
Several others in my family had various versions of their burrito which they really liked. My youngest son had a quesadilla which he said was slightly better than Taco Bell.
The prices are very reasonable. I would visit again but I would not order the nachos.
They have a unisex bathroom which was clean. I extremely dislike using a unisex bathroom but I give them credit for having it in good condition.

text: Worked here before not a place you wanna get food from. Ask to see the back room yikes. Alot of big roaches there sometimes you can see it running around. The fish is frozen comes in a bag. Nachos chips are not fresh. They re heat it in a microwave. I was cheated out of my tips every night. I was never given a shirt for work. Plus I got sick and was fired for calling in. I also was offered to smoke drugs in the back with the boys on my 2nd day of work. They took all my tips money and I never got one dime or penny. Not a place I'd support. Lunch was never offered to me to eat for lunch as an employee meal. I sat there watch my co workers eat and never bother to ask if I wanted something to eat or drink! I think I didn't deserve to have been fired. The people there are lazy. I never had a interview I sat there for an hour then was told you do this you do that put that there that goes here and there and that was it. I never knew who my boss was. I was fired by text message and it was not sent to me it was sent to a 3rd party. Someone else had to tell me I no longer work there. So unprofessional. They steal my tips. It was a birthday dinner

Hoku seemed to have changed a lot, from seafood theme to more contemporary fine dining.

text:
Excellent food and exceptional service! We will be back. We opted for 4 course menu and decided to share the dishes among 3 of us as they were generous portions vs. the grand 8 course menu. The executive chef has worked at various 3 michelin star restaurants including but not limited to French Laundry, Per Se, El Bulli, Gordon Ramsey, Alinea, and The Fat Duck.

text:
Hoku's is, in opinion, the best Sunday brunch buffet in Honolulu or anywhere else on Oahu. This is the only buffet on Oahu that  has all you can eat Maine lobsters. When I was there on April 22nd I had 4. Some things are not on the buffet line and must be ordered through your server. Two examples of this are true Mainstays of Hoku's; the fried ahi poke musubi (the best musubi I have ever had) and work fried soft shell crab.
The prime rib and rack of lamb we're a perfect medium rare, juicy and tender. The king crab legs were succulent. I loved the shrimp and asparagus tempura as well as the smoked salmon eggs Benedict. They have pokes, shrimp cocktail, sushi, ahi sashimi, salads and much more. All is of exceptional quality.
For dessert I had the best bread pudding and coconut cake I have ever had!
Along with this is extraordinary service, from the lovely, professional and efficient host people, the extraordinary servers, Lisa and Georgia and all other employees that I encountered.
I will be back!

text: I had heard about the huge portions and the over-the-top calorie count, and thought that I'd probably never eat here. Today, I'm glad to say that I was pleasantly surprised with the Skinnylicious menu. The steak medallions (440 cal) were delicious, cooked to perfection, and accompanied by tasty mashed potatoes, mushrooms, asparagus, and tomatoes. The portion size was just right, too, so that I was full but not stuffed. My mojito (100 cal) was refreshing, too! The only critique that I have is that the crusty sourdough bread is really crusty; it's tough to get through the exterior to the yummy insides. It was also nice that we didn't have a long wait to be seated (pretty good for Thursday dinner rush). Great atmosphere, friendly servers, and convenient location mean that we'll be back.

text: Went here for the first time with my daughter.  While at our table the fire alarm went off in error.  The loud noise terrified my daughter and the manager found out about my special needs daughter and how she wasn't doing to well with the sound that by this time was off.  Before we ordered the manager walked up to my table knelt down to my daughter and told her I'm sorry the alarm scared you, and asked her if she liked monkeys.   My daughter said yes and she was given a small monkey bear. The manager then said if you have room I'll get you a piece of cake.  The way she helped assure my daughter was going to be okay was heartwarming.  Even though the alarm was an off putting experience.  The manager made the experience great.  In the end my daughter ate everything on her plate.  Something that rarely happens after one of her meltdowns, she got to take home her new favorite monkey and I made sure she got some cake.

text:
Part of the 5-star rating is based on the fact that this location actually has the FULL Cheesecake Factory menu, unlike the other location on the island.  Yes!!!!  I'm finally able to order my favorite dish (White Bean Chicken Chili) on the island!!!  I'm so happy!!!

So happy, in fact, that I went there about twice a week for about two or three weeks right after they opened.  It helped that I was on vacation, perfect timing.  I definitely recommend that, even though this location definitely gives less rice with the chili than mainland locations I've frequented.  It definitely works though.  Usually, there's just enough rice.  Other times, I have to be diligent in doling out spoonfuls with the beans and chili.

Two other favorites are the Thai Lettuce Wraps-often ordered as my meal and the Carmel Pecan Turtle Cheesecake.  I don't eat the chocolate on top since I'm not a huge chocolate fan.  A close second is the Red Velvet cheesecake.  Both are very rich and I rarely eat either all at once.

TIP:  Since this is a new location, it has been even more packed than some other locations during the lunch hours, so I'd be patient with the wait.  The line often extends outside for 20min or so.

text:
Upon entry, we saw a decent crowd of customers and the hustle of staff.  We were seated within 3 minutes and service arrived shortly.  Our server was very patient, friendly, and incredibly helpful. I am terrible with names, i would have  loved to commend her by name.

Okay.. the food.
Usually my family and i share and give taste samples..  maybe they were too hungry, i dont know. They inhaled their incredibly large portions, and i admit, i was enjoying mine too.  I had a combination plate that consisted of chicken, mashed potatoes, and thick cuts of steak, smothered in mushrooms.

The food was good.
Prices are a bit high, but quality is nice.  You get both quality and quantity.

Of course cheesecakes will make you gain 20lbs by looking at their beautiful display case, standing and trying to decide what to order.    That was the most difficult part of our time there.

This is a wonderful place to celebrate, have a family meal, datenight or out of state guests.  Regardless, my kids and i want more.

text: Husband and I typically frequent this location (kapolei) and order two items consistently. First the grilled salmon and the other skinnylicious medallions. This evening I had family emergency to attend to so left abruptly without my phone. My husband picked me up with our young granddaughters on his way to work. We decided to order from this location with hesitation. Past few times our order was inconsistent. However with situation at hand we really had heart set on the medallion meal. As i didn't have my phone and husband running late to work he had a coworker pick him up and left me with cash enough for the meal (medallions and cheesecake) and tip. I waited for a server over 30 minutes and asked an employee to get a server for me and he ignored me. Luckily a patron came along and helped me get a server as I had the girls sleeping in the car. Finally a server comes out with my food and I check it because past few times they have jipped me on the asparagus and I added a note on order to please put full servings of asparagus. I could not believe what I saw when I opened lid to entree, after the day I had and seeing how messed up the order was I wanted to cry so frustrated. It was smaller portion than normal, even for skinny, and if only had like 4 soggy skinny pieces of aspargus and didn't see mushrooms. It was just mush. I have seen TV dinners look better. Not to mention it was cold.Very disappoining for being expensive. I told manager and instead of being honest or valuing a repetive customer he was rude and arrogant kept claiming that's the skinny size and didn't even acknowledge how horrible it was. I truly wish I was able to take a pic of it, as my words dont properly express how horrible it was. He offered to redo it, I figured if that dish is going to be an issue try something simple like the salmon, I had already been there an hour. Then I find out its 10 dollars more, the previous order with cheesecake was 27 and then I learn it's now 35 before tip. Manager was very rude about the whole thing and besides not valuing its customers, belittling me because my husband left me with what was expected and I had no phone with me. He tried to say it was my fault for not calling and saying I was there. It does NOT say please call to let us know you're here. Also, that does not explain the poor execution of the meal.  I waited for an hour and had to leave empty handed, and feeling belittled by the managers behavior. Food was not good quality he knows it and didn't honor it. I ended up having to go to cpk where I should have gone in first place. They are consistent with food and value its customers. I strongly suggest be cautious if you decide to eat at this place and I recommend anywhere else but cheesecake factory kapolei.
